<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1410 GMT, September 12 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH -- At least three people were wounded by gunfire as
Cambodian government supporters and opposition protesters clashed
Saturday just off Phnom Penh's main business street, witnesses
said.
</P>
<P>
A boy and a man in his twenties were wounded in their legs by
gun shots, while another man was bleeding from a chest wound,
after a volley of shots fired by the pro-government demonstrators
near the city's Monivong Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
Cambodian opposition parties had earlier called off a planned
Sunday protest rally after 5,000 supporters of the Cambodian
People's Party (CPP) demonstrated on Saturday, bringing the
worsened tension between the government and opposition into the
sixth day. (Cambodia-Demonstration)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Following its threat to take revenge on the Afghan
Taliban militia, Iran announced Saturday to launch its biggest
military maneuver involving 200,000 troops near its eastern border
with Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here, the army's commander of
land forces Abdolali Pourshasb said that 40 percent of the three
divisions have been deployed along the border during the past
month under the command of supreme leader and Commander-in-Chief
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
He said that the maneuver, code-named Zoulfaqar 2, would start
at the end of September, and that the troops would remain in the
border areas after the week-long maneuver. (Iran-Maneuver)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- At least 13 Palestinians were injured in clashes
with Israeli soldiers on Saturday as tension has mounted in the
West Bank following the killing of two Palestinians on Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian sources said 10 Palestinians injured in Ramallah
and three in Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel Radio reported that an explosive device went
off near an army vehicle Friday night, but it did not give further
details. (Palestinians-Israel-Tension)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LUANDA -- A UNITA force in Angola has captured Maquela do
Zombo, a border town in northern Angola under the help of the
rebels from neighboring Democratic Congo.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said the Tutsi-led rebels used at least five 160 mm
cannons to bomb the town Thursday, offering aid to the fighters of
the opposition movement of the National Union for Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA), the Journal of Angola charged
Saturday. (Angola-Congo Rebels-UNITA)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- Nigeria has denied massing troops to the disputed
Bakassi Peninsula on its border with Cameroun, media reports said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Headquarters said in a statement in Lagos Friday
that reports to the effect was "misleading and untrue", adding
that Nigeria was still resolved to settle the dispute through
peaceful means. (Nigeria-Bakassi-Denial)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- South African Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo
Saturday dismissed reports of an attempted coup in Lesotho as
unfounded, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
"It was just some problems in the army itself, it's not a coup
as such. We think the situation is not as bad as earlier
reported," said Nzo, who has been in Mauritius attending a two-day
meeting of the Southern African Development Community (SADC)'s
council of ministers. (SAfrica-Lesotho-Coup Denial) 
</P>
</TEXT>
