<HEADLINE> Mandela Stresses Coordination on Congo (K) Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PORT LOUIS, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Visiting South African
President Nelson Mandela Saturday reiterated coordination between
the Southern African Development Community (SADC) and the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) regarding the Congo crisis.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of Tanzania, Zambia and Mozambique have
agreed that there should be coordination between the summit in
Pretoria, South Africa, and the meetings held in Victoria Falls
of Zimbabwe on the crisis in the Democratic Republic of Congo
(DRC), Mandela told a press conference here in the Mauritian
capital Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"We should coordinate with Salim Ahmed Salim, the
Secretary-General of the Organization of African Unity" on the
issue, he added.
</P>
<P>
He believed that progress will be made on how to normalizepthe
situation in the DRC and the implementation of the peace
initiatives during the forthcoming SADC summit scheduled on
Sunday and Monday.
</P>
<P>
Since the armed revolt broke out on August 2 in the east of
the DRC, a couple of meetings of the SADC countries have been
held on how to resolve the crisis in the vast central African
country.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, who is also chairman of the SADC summit, recalled the
efforts made by the regional grouping, saying that many
initiatives have been taken by the various meetings on the Congo.
</P>
<P>
The summit in Pretoria called by Mandela in late August
decided on an immediate cease-fire, a standstill of all the
troops involved in the conflict, the withdrawal of foreign troops
and the start of negotiations which will eventually lead to the
introduction of a democratic government.
</P>
<P>
During the 12th Non-Aligned Movement summit in Durban, South
Africa in early September, Mandela said: "We decided that the
troops inside the Congo must meet to sort out the problems
themselves," referring to those Rwandan and Ugandan troops which
are allegedly backing the rebels, and the SADC alliance composed
J3qZimbabwean, Namibian and Angolan troops which were trying to
prop up the 16-month-old Laurent Kabila government.
</P>
<P>
However, Mandela said it is not enough to simply take
initiatives. "We still have to go to the field where the
commanders are, to bring them together and explain to them the
decisions made in Pretoria and why the decisions are made," the
president noted.
</P>
<P>
"Innocent people are dying, the infrastructure in the country
has been destroyed and people want to get on with their lives,"
he appealed, adding that "they could only get it on the condition
of peace."
</P>
<P>
There has been disagreement on the approaches to the
settlement of the crisis in Democratic Congo between those led by
South African President Mandela who are for diplomacy and those
headed by Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe who advocate
military intervention.
</P>
<P>
Nontheless, Mandela announced earlier that he understo@ the
steps taken by Zimbabwe whose troK0_.H4ad been invited by Kabila's
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
