<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnians Begin Casting Votes in Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Bosnia's second national
election since the 1995 Dayton peace accord was signed began
Saturday under international supervision.
</P>
<P>
A total of 83 candidates, parties and coalitions are listed on
the the ballots, among which the individual candidates are running
for the three posts on the joint presidency -- one Muslim, one
Serb and one Croat -- while parties compete for seats in a
national parliament and parliaments in each entity.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of polling stations opened late due to a computer
glitch. But the early turnout appears to be steady and some
officials estimated it at 80 percent by the time polls close
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
More than 2.75 million Croats, Moslems and Serbs were
registered to vote, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The election will be a step forward toward normalization and
democratization of Bosnia-Herzegovina, said Carlos Westendorp,
the European high representative in Bosnia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
