<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghana Faces Major Water Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Ghana's water supply system is
likely to face a major problem next year as most of the country's
water sources are drying up due to inadequate rainfall, said a
report reaching here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
A report by the Ghana Focus said the problem might be worsened
by the approaching long dry season as well as constraints placed
on the existing water supply system.
</P>
<P>
Jonathan Nunoo, the Managing Director of the Ghana Water and
Sewerage Corporation was quoted as saying that inadequate
resources are preventing the corporation from undertaking
maintenance works as well as expanding its networks to cover the
whole country. Thus, it is forced to fall on aquifers to supply
water to some communities.
</P>
<P>
Nunoo made the remarks Thursday in Accra while meeting with
Claire Short, the British Secretary of State for International
Development, who was on a four-day visit to Ghana for talks with
government officials and inspection of British government funded
projects.
</P>
<P>
Inadequate rainfall has forced Ghana's hydropower plants to
reduce their output throughout last summer, causing serious power
shortage for both industries and residents.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
