<DOCNO> XIE19980913.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Has Telephone Conversation with U.S. President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The appointment of Yevgeny
Primakov as prime minister was an unequivocal proof of Russia's
commitment to a free market course, said Russian President Boris
Yeltsin in a telephone conversation with U.S. President Bill
Clinton on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Russian presidential press service said in a statement that
Yeltsin stressed the permanence of Russia's foreign policy,
including a mutually beneficial and equal partnership with the
United States; the consistency in the carrying out of reforms;
and the lack of an alternative to a market course.
</P>
<P>
During the conversation Yeltsin spoke about recent events in
the country, including the government's appointments.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, in return, said that the United States supports
Russian as before on its reform path. It is ready to continue the
most active cooperation with new Russian government, including
within the framework of the Gore-Primakov commission, the press
statement said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin named Primakov as premier's nominee on Thursday after
the State Duma, or lower house of parliament, rejected Viktor
Chernomyrdin as candidate for prime minister twice. The Duma
overwhelmingly confirmed Primakov on Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
