<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt, France Press Ahead Joint Peace Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said Saturday that high-level Egyptian and French officials
will start meetings on Monday in Paris to discuss steps to enforce
their joint initiative to push forward the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
The initiative was launched in May by Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak and French President Jacques Chirac who called for holding
an international conference to salvage the Mideast peace process
which has been languishing for 18 months.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks have came to a stop when Israel
began building Jewish settlement on the Arab East Jerusalem in
March 1997.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will also pave the way for the meeting of Moussa
and his French counterpart Hubert Vedrine in New York on the
sidelines of the 53rd United Nations General Assembly this month.
</P>
<P>
Telling reporters here, Moussa added that Egypt and France
agree that they should go on with putting into force their peace
bid as long as no progress was made in the mediations long
spearheaded by the United State.
</P>
<P>
The American efforts have been frustrated by Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's refusal to accept a 13 percent
pullback plan in the occupied West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Paris meeting will discuss arrangements for the
international conference, Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian delegation to leave here Sunday for Paris includes
Assistant Foreign Minister Ahmed Abul Kheir and the official in
charge of the Mideast at the foreign minister's office Ali Erfan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
