<HEADLINE> House Speaker Says President Needs Chance to Respond </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Newt Gingrich, Speaker of
the U.S. House of Representatives said Saturday that President
Bill Clinton needs a chance to answer Independent Counsel Kenneth
Starr's report and the judiciary committee needs time to process
Starr's allegations.
</P>
<P>
"I think you cannot render... any judgment until you have given
the president a chance to respond and given the judiciary
committee a chance to do its job," Gingrich was quoting by The
Associated Press as telling a campaign stop in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
On the lurid details in the report, Gingrich said, "It's
terrible that it's about this kind of topic, but it is a good
thing that the American people can fully participate in seeing
exactly the same information that their members of Congress are
seeing."
</P>
<P>
"I suspect by the end of this weekend, this will be the most
widely disseminated government report in history," he said.
</P>
<P>
The graphic text of the report was disturbing, Gingrich said,
adding he nonetheless felt it was necessary because of the nature
of the president's behavior.
</P>
<P>
"I wish he had told us the truth from the beginning, and we
would not have read many things that have no place in public
literature," he said. 
</P>
