<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Insists on Israel's Acceptance of U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat has insisted that Israel accept the U.S. proposal so that
the peace process could be moved forward, said a senior
Palestinian official Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Saeb Erekat, Palestinian peace negotiator and minister of
local government, told the Voice of Palestine radio that Arafat,
during his second meeting Saturday in Nablus with the U.S. peace
envoy Dennis Ross, said the U.S. proposal is the basis for moving
the peace process forward.
</P>
<P>
Among other things, the U.S. proposal, which has not been
announced so far but rejected by Israel, asks Israel to pull out
from 13.1 percent of the West Bank territories during the
second-phase troop redeployment.
</P>
<P>
After his first round of talks with Ross three days ago, Arafat
also informed the U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright that
any discussions concerning the peace process must be based on the
U.S. proposal which must be regarded as a whole package, Erekat
said.
</P>
<P>
Such discussions must include the interim issues, security
issues, the second and the third stage redeployments, the
timetable for redeployments and the U.S. guarantees for the third
redeployment, Erekat said.
</P>
<P>
Erekat also disclosed that what has been discussed during
Ross' current mission is a review of the U.S. proposal to
determine which points need a mechanism for their implementation
and more work.
</P>
<P>
He said the ongoing peace talks between Arafat and Ross and
between Ross and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu also
touched such interim issues as the safe passage linking the West
Bank and Gaza Strip, the Gaza airport and seaport and the release
of Palestinian prisoners held by Israel.
</P>
<P>
Erekat expressed the hope that Ross will come back from his
talks with the Israelis with a clear "yes" on all these issues.
</P>
<P>
Ross returned to the region Wednesday and held his first round
of talks with Arafat in Ramallah shortly after his arrival.
</P>
<P>
Ross holds the third round of talks with Netanyahu here
Saturday night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
