<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-12 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Decides on Military Deployment Along Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Supreme Council of
National Security (SCNS) on Saturday decided to strengthen its
forces along the border with Afghanistan in order to prevent
possible challenge by the Afghan Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
The SCNS made the decision in a meeting presided over by
President Mohammad Khatami and with participation of senior
political and military officials in the wake of the confirmation
of the killing of nine Iranian diplomats in Afghanistan, Tehran
radio reported.
</P>
<P>
An official close to the meeting said that the deployment was
aimed at protecting Iran's territorial integrity and preventing
any possible challenge by the Taliban along Iran's border with
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The official, whose name was not given, said the SCNS reviewed
present developments in Afghanistan and exchanged views on plans
and reports by members of the council.
</P>
<P>
The council commissioned all relevant Iranian authorities to
consider every possible channel and to adopt appropriate measures
for protecting Iran's national interests, and maintaining
regional peace and security.
</P>
<P>
The official stressed that Iran would proceed with arrangements
for establishing peace and security in the region.
</P>
<P>
During the past month, the Iranian army and the Islamic
Revolutionary Guards Corps (IRGC) have built up their military
presence on the country's eastern border with Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The IRGC deployed 70,000 troops along the northeastern border
following a ground-breaking war game on September 1, while the
army dispatched three divisions to the southeastern border.
</P>
<P>
The army Saturday also announced to launch its biggest
maneuvers involving 200,000 troops in the border area.
</P>
<P>
Observers noted that military deployment indicated a possible
military confrontation between Iran and the Taliban militia, as
senior Iranian officials have vowed to take revenge for the
killing of Iranian diplomats.
</P>
<P>
Local dailies said that a war in Afghanistan would be
"unavoidable" for Iran, though it would be unhelpful for
Khatami's declared policy of detente.
</P>
<P>
As the Taliban forces are advancing in the Bamyan province in
northern Afghanistan, the center of Iran-backed Shiite Muslims,
the only possible way to stop ethnic cleansing in Bamyan is
massive Iranian assistance, the pro-government newspaper Iran
Daily said in an editorial on Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
