<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Belgium airlines will operate four regular
passenger and four cargo flights each between Egypt and Belgium,
Egypt's English daily Egyptian Mail reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The two national airlines will be the authorized airlines
between the two countries, according to Egyptian Minister of
Transport and Communications Soliman Metwalli Soliman.
</P>
<P>
He added that the two countries had reached an agreement on
this regard during negotiations between them in Brussels
recently.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The Islamic Development Bank (IDB) has offered to
lend Lebanon up to 3 million U.S. dollars to finance small and
medium-sized industrial projects, local newspapers reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Daoud Suleiman Al-Bourshid, head of an IDB delegation visiting
Beirut said "we are ready to finance the purchase of industrial
machinery, raw materials as well as financing trade and export
transactions worth between 50,000 and up to 3 million dollars."
</P>
<P>
The Saudi Arabia-based IDB previously offered Lebanon loans of
418 million dollars to build a new campus for the state-run
Lebanese University.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon's Deputy Central Bank Governor Nasser Saidi
has denied reports that any Yugoslav state funds have been
transferred en masse to be deposited for safe-keeping in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese newspaper Asharq Al-Awasat Friday quoted Saidi as
saying that an "honor charter" and strict measures agreed by
members of the Lebanese banking system "prohibit this kind of
operation which tends to tarnish the reputation of Lebanese banks
at a time international confidence in them is increasing."
</P>
<P>
He added that a special committee is working hard and daily to
deter "money laundering and other suspicious (financial)
operations."
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports here said that Serbian President Slobodan
Milosevic had transferred Yugoslav federation funds from a safe
haven in Cyprus to Lebanon in view of Cyprus' attempts to join
the European Union which is leading pressure for economic
sanctions on Belgrade over the crisis in Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
