<HEADLINE> (URGENT) White House Issues Second Rebuttal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 12 (Xinhua) -- A day after the release
of Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's report, the White House
fought back Saturday with a second rebuttal attacking each of the
prosecutor's allegations and said his arguments were focused on
sex.
</P>
<P>
While saying Clinton's actions were wrong, his lawyers said
"such acts do not even approach the Constitutional test of
impeachment -- treason, bribery or other high crimes and
misdemeanors."
</P>
<P>
"After impaneling grand juries and leasing office space in
three jurisdictions and investigating virtually every aspect of
the president's business, financial, political, official and
ultimately, personal life, the Office of Independent Counsel has
presented to the House a referral that no prosecutor would present
to any jury," the White House said.
</P>
<P>
Starr has argued that the case against Clinton was about
perjury, subornation of perjury, witness tampering and obstruction
of justice. But, the president's lawyers contended that Starr's
report demonstrates that "it is plain that sex is precisely what
this four-and-a-half-year investigation has boiled down to."
</P>
<P>
"The referral is so loaded with irrelevant and unnecessary
graphic and salacious allegations that only one conclusion is
possible: its principal purpose is to damage the president," the
rebuttal said.
</P>
<P>
The wrongfulness of Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky
is not in dispute, Clinton's lawyers said, "And yet that
relationship is the relentless focus of virtually every page of
the OIC's (Office of Independent Counsel) referral." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
