<DOCNO> XIE19980913.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Lawmakers to Focus on National Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton, after what he called "an exhausting and difficult week"
in the capital, on Saturday urged lawmakers to "stay focused" on
national issues such as health care, economy and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot lose sight of our primary mission, which is to work
for the American people," Clinton said in his weekly radio address
to the nation.
</P>
<P>
Clinton made no direct mention of the sex and perjury scandal,
but he began his remarks by saying "it has been an exhausting and
difficult week in the capital, not only for me but for many
others."
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who was accused of committing possible impeachable
offenses in a lurid report by independent counsel Kenneth Starr
released to Congress and the public on Friday, wanted the American
people shift their focus from the scandal.
</P>
<P>
"The most important thing to do now is to stay focused on the
issues the American people sent us here to deal with, from health
care, to the economy, to terrorism," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton announced 8.7 million U.S. dollars in federal grants to
93 community groups to fund programs designed to discourage
drug, alcohol and tobacco use by young people.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's drug policy director, Barry McCaffrey, said the
intention was to encourage more communities to form anti-drug
coalitions. He said there were now 4,000 such coalitions and the
goal was to raise the number to about 14,000 by 2005.
</P>
<P>
While overall illegal drug use has declined in the United
States, use by children has increased. McCaffrey said the
number of eighth graders who smoked marijuana or drank alcohol
had tripled over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also committed to continue to invest in education. "We
have to have smaller classes, more teachers, modernized schools,
all the classrooms hooked up to the Internet, and higher
standards," he repeated his the plan of his administration.
</P>
<P>
In his radio address, Clinton also urged lawmakers to enact
legislation to help the International Monetary Fund (IMF) deal
with the financial crises gripping Asia and Russia.
</P>
<P>
Clinton asked Congress to pass legislation that would give the
IMF 18 billion dollars to replenish its coffers, which have been
depleted by a number of multibillion-dollar bailouts.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he would discuss the global economy with Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin in New York on Monday and urged Congress to
approve the IMF funding so that "America does not become a sea of
prosperity in an ocean of distress." 
</P>
</TEXT>
