<HEADLINE> Regional Seminar in Nepal Stresses Peaceful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Participants in a regional
seminar held here Sunday stressed the need of peaceful
reunification of the two Koreas, Nepal's official RSS news agency
said.
</P>
<P>
The one-day seminar, jointly organized by the Korea
Reunification Support Committee of Nepal and the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), was represented by Nepal,
India, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka, Pakistan, DPRK and Thailand, RSS
said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the seminar, Beni Bahadur Karki, chairman of Nepal's
National Assembly, said that his country is in favor of peaceful
reunification of the two Koreas.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need of talks between the statesmen of the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Man Mohan Adhikari, president of the main opposition Communist
Party of Nepal (United Marxism-Leninism, CPN-UML), noted that
economic development is possible only after reunification is
achieved in a peaceful manner.
</P>
<P>
Nepali MP C.P. Mainali observed that the efforts made by the
DPRK for reunification are highly praiseworthy.
</P>
<P>
Dilip Baruwa, general secretary of the Indian Communist Party
(ML), spoke of the need to apply the juche ideology to initiate
the process of reunification.
</P>
<P>
Indian MP Shiv Shankar stressed the need of peaceful talks to
materialize the efforts initiated by DPRK leader Kim Jong Il.
</P>
<P>
Other representatives also laid emphasis on the need to move
ahead with the process of peaceful reunification, RSS said.
</P>
<P>
The Korean Peninsula has been divided since the end of the
Second World War in August 1945. 
</P>
</TEXT>
