<HEADLINE> Roundup: Lesotho Coup Denied, But Problems Do </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Although both Lesotho
and South Africa have denied a military coup in Lesotho, it iw
believed that signs of a crisis do exist in the land-locked
kingdom.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela said Saturday that
there was no crisis in Lesotho, claiming there was no need to be
alarmed by the situation in Ldsotho.
</P>
<P>
Mandela made the remarks while he was visiting Mauritius where
he is also to attend the Southern African Development Community
(SADC) summit due to open on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He said he had spoken to Lesotho King Letsie III, quoting the
king as saying that reports of the arrest of Lesotho Prime
minister Pathakili Mosisili were false.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Lesotho Foreign Minister Tom Thabane, who was
in Mauritius attending a SADC council ministersPmeeting in
prepartion for the summit, confirmed that the Lesotho cabinet led
by Prime Minister Pathakili Mosisili was still in full control of
the country.
</P>
<P>
Thabane said that after some reports that Lesotho's army chief
Li%utenant-General Makhula Mosakheng and 28 senior military
officers quit late Friday amid signs of a coup and confusion over
who was in control of the country.
</P>
<P>
Thabane's South African counterpart Alfred Nzo, who chaired
the SADC council ministers meeting, also told reporters that
reports of a coup in Lesotho were unfounded.
</P>
<P>
However, Nzo confirmed that South African Defense Minister Joe
Modise would arrive in Maseru, the troubled capital of Lesotho,
late Saturday to mediate disputes between the cabinet and army of
the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
According to latest information reaching here Sunday, Modise
has held a series of meetings with Lesotho government officials
and military representatives.
</P>
<P>
As soon as his arrival in the mountain kingdom, Modise went
into talks with Prime Minister Pathakili Mosisili, his deputy
Kelebone Maope, and Foreign Minister Tom Thabane, South African
High Commission officials said Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
Modise then went to the Defense Ministry for a meeting with
the newly installed head of army, Brigadier Anthony Thibeli. He
also met Mosakheng, who, together with 28 senior officers,
resigned on Friday night with immediate effect.
</P>
<P>
Mosakheng did not mention the reason of his resignation.
However, political observers and diplomats believed that
Mosakheng made the resignation announcement under duress.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources, who asked not be named, quoted Thibeli as
saying that he was unsure of his status and that the South
African government still regarded Mosakheng as head of the
Lesotho army.
</P>
<P>
It is generally believed that Lesotho, troubled with
opposition's allegation of May electoral fraud by the ruling
Lesotho Congress for Democracy since early August, is currently
under government's control, but situation in the small country
was extremely fluid in the capital.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, Botswana and Zimbabwe, that have jointly made
an investigation about the alleged Lesotho election fraud, are
expected to put their investigation report on the agenda of the
SADC summit due to be held in Mauritius on Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
