<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Crown Prince Visits Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Crown Prince
Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz left for Britain Sunday on an official
visit as part of a seven-nation tour, the Kuwait News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
British diplomats in Saudi Arabia said Saturday that during
his four-day visit, Prince Abdullah, also Deputy Prime Minister
and Commander of the National Guards, would meet with British
Prime Minister Tony Blair and other officials on a number of
security matters in the Gulf region, the stalled Middle East
peace process and bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The diplomats said that the Saudi and British leaders would
also discuss the developments in Afghanistan and Kosovo, as
well as ways to enhance bilateral economic, investment and
defense cooperation.
</P>
<P>
While the Saudi government has kept a low-key over Abdullah's
visit, the second since 1988, it was attached great importance
by British officials in London.
</P>
<P>
A senior British Foreign Office official has said that the
Saudi Crown Prince's visit would be "extremely important" as the
Gulf kingdom is "strategically the major country in the region."
</P>
<P>
Bilateral relations between Britain and Saudi Arabia have been
strengthened since the Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, the Gulf heavyweight, is a very important
market and the largest trading partner in the Middle East
for Britain. Bilateral trade stood at 4.5 billion U.S. dollars
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Britain exported to Saudi Arabia goods worth some 4.2 billion
U.S. dollars in 1996, up 51 percent compared with the figure in
1995.
</P>
<P>
Since 1988, Saudi Arabia has signed several arms deals and
defense cooperation treaties with Britain with a total value of
about 44 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Under these agreements, the British government had supplied
Saudi Arabia with defense equipment, military aircraft and
training facilities worth billions of U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement by the Saudi Royal Palace, Prince
Abdullah's British tour will be followed by a similar
three-day visit to France where he will hold talks with
French President Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
Prince Abdullah, accompanied by Saudi Foreign Minister Prince
Saud Al-Faisal, Minister of Finance and National Economy Ibrahim
Al-Assaf and Minister of Commerce Osama Faqih, will also head to
the United States, Japan, China, South Korea and Pakistan.
</P>
</TEXT>
