<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier Li Lanqing Inspects Flood-Hit Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Li
Lanqing has called for still greater efforts to ensure good
sanitation conditions and prevent diseases and epidemics in the
flood-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
During an inspection tour of northeast China's Heilongjiang and
Jilin provinces and northern Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region
September 11-13, Li also said that a good job must be done of
reconstructing primary and middle schools destroyed by floods so
that teaching can be resumed.
</P>
<P>
"You have already suffered so much from severe floods and must
not be afflicted by diseases and epidemics," said Li, who is also
a member of the Standing Committee of the Political Bureau of the
Central Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC). He was
addressing the people in a rural county near Daqing, an oil city
that was ravaged by floods this summer.
</P>
<P>
"You should pay particular attention to sanitation and disease
prevention and control," he said. "Only with good health can you
rebuild your homes."
</P>
<P>
Li, who said he was delighted by the news that no epidemics
have broken out in the flooded areas, warned people against
slackening their vigilance, saying that preventing diseases and
epidemics is a long-term task.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to several primary schools set up in tents and
temporary classrooms. Li urged the children to treasure their
hard-earned study opportunities and work harder to contribute to
the motherland in the future.
</P>
<P>
Schools and classrooms must be repaired or rebuilt; and in some
cases, residential houses or office buildings should be rented out
as classrooms before the arrival of winter to enable children to
study indoors and spare them the chill of winter, the vice-premier
urged.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
