<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tax Reform Dominates Australian TV Election Debate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister
John Howard and Labor Party Leader Kim Beazley argued heatedly
during Sunday night's election debate dominated by tax reform.
</P>
<P>
In his opening address to the 60-minute-long debate, Prime
Minister John Howard, leader of the Australian Liberal Party,
boasted of the economic competence of his government, and
repeatedly managed to steer the debate back on to his tax plan.
</P>
<P>
Kim Beazley, leader of the Australian Labor Party, performed
best when he widened the televised debate to social issues like
jobs, health and a vision for Australia.
</P>
<P>
Howard said the government had achieved a budget surplus 12
months ahead of schedule and brought interest rates to their
lowest level for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Beazley responded by saying Howard inherited high economic
growth and high jobs growth from the Paul Keating's government in
1996.
</P>
<P>
The opposition party said the election campaign needed to be
about more than the economy, and that people needed the security
of a decent public health system.
</P>
<P>
Howard was forced on the defensive over his failure to make
inroads into unemployment, and in particular youth unemployment,
after he promised in 1996 election campaign that his party was the
only party with a plan to bring down the youth jobless rate.
</P>
<P>
The jobless rate stands at 8.1 percent and youth jobless rate
at 28.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Every time Beazley tried to widen the debate to issues such as
health and jobs, Howard brought the argument back to tax, saying
tax reform was essential to providing the money for jobs and
social services.
</P>
<P>
While Howard scored the early blows on tax reform, Beazley
finished stronger with his vision for Australia.
</P>
<P>
In their closing arguments at Sunday night's debate, the two
leaders were asked about their vision for the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
Howard said he hoped for an economically secure society, while
Beazley stressed racial tolerance and unity.
</P>
<P>
Although the prime minister did say he wanted a tolerant
Australia in the future but the race issue is something the prime
minister would try to avoid.
</P>
<P>
Howard has been accused of being partly responsible for the
rise of racism One Nation Party led by Pauline Hanson as he
repeatedly refused to condemn Hanson's racist remarks for about
one year in late 1996 and early 1997.
</P>
<P>
Beazley said he hoped for security, prosperity and fairness.
</P>
<P>
"I want Australia as a fair society and a secure society,"
Beazley said.
</P>
<P>
"I want an Australia in which every Australian values every
other Australian - where that good attitude towards mateship is an
expression of genuine affection for every Australian no matter
what their backgrounds, their cultural background, their racial
background."
</P>
<P>
After the debate, both Howard and Beazley camps said their man
was the winner of the debate, but Howard refused the Labor Party's
appeal for a second debate with his rival.
</P>
<P>
Beazley last week condemned the limit of one debate as absurd,
saying Sunday night's debate was too early as there were three
weeks away from October 3, the polling date announced by Howard on
August 30.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
