<HEADLINE> Popularize Common Tongue: ``People's Daily'' (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 13 (Xinhua) -- "People's Daily", China's
leading newspaper, tomorrow will publish a commentator's article
calling for greater efforts to popularize the use of standard
Chinese, commonly known as putonghua or Mandarin.
</P>
<P>
The article notes that the popularization of Putonghua is a
landmark of the development level of both material as well as
socialist ethical and cultural progress, and is of major
importance for promoting economic growth and social progress.
</P>
<P>
"After years of effort, we have made remarkable progress in
spreading the use of Putonghua, but owing to China's vast
territory, large population and imbalanced economic development,
Putonghua is far from being uniformly used in the country as a
whole," the article notes.
</P>
<P>
With the in-depth progress of China's reform and opening up, as
well as more frequent exchanges both internally and
internationally, an increasing number of people have come to
recognize that the barriers caused by dialects have become
detrimental to social development.
</P>
<P>
The practice of many developed countries has also proved that
the popularization of common spoken languages and the
standardization of language are basic conditions for the
universalization of education, the development of science and
technology and the promotion of the modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
More efforts should be made to enable people to become
increasingly aware of the importance and urgency of speaking
Putonghua so as to help create an atmosphere in which every person
can communicate in the common tongue.
</P>
<P>
The spread of Putonghua is not aimed at abolishing dialects,
which on specific occasions have their own uses and cultural
values, the article says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980913.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Popularize Common Tongue: ``People's Daily''  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Instead, it is for the purpose of enabling people to master a
more widely and commonly used language apart from dialects so as
to break down communication barriers, and facilitate their study and
work," it says.
</P>
<P>
The article urges governments at all levels to put the
promotion of Putonghua high on their work agenda, noting that
Putonghua should be used as the common teaching and campus
language.
</P>
<P>
Civil servants should play a leading role in speaking
Putonghua, while radio announcers and TV anchorpersons should
constantly improve their Putonghua to make themselves role models
for the whole of society, the commentary says.
</P>
<P>
It acknowledges that China is now in an unprecedentedly good
condition to popularize Putonghua, as there is not only a strong
social demand for the use of Putonghua but also conveniences
provided by the country's rapid development on all fronts.
</P>
<P>
"We should strive to seize this opportunity to promote
Putonghua in order to make it the common speech throughout the
country by the middle of the next century," the commentator's
article says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
