<HEADLINE> China to Unveil Securities Law at Earliest Possible Date </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 13 (Xinhua) -- China will unveil its first
securities law at the earliest possible date, in an effort to
promote a stable and healthy development of the fledgling
securities market, an official source said here today.
</P>
<P>
The draft of the Securities Law is being revised and will be
made public as soon as possible, Li Yining, head of the drafting
team, told a symposium on China's joint-stock enterprises and the
growth of the securities market, which opened today.
</P>
<P>
However, Li, a noted economist who first advocated the
shareholding system in China, did not provide a timetable for the
unveiling of the law, which was first drafted in 1992 and tabled
for official discussion in 1993.
</P>
<P>
He said he is full of confidence about the development
prospects for the Chinese securities market, which already
includes more than 800 listed companies.
</P>
<P>
Since 1991, listed companies have raised from the securities
market funds valued at a total of 322.28 billion yuan,
including 148.9 billion yuan pooled through the issue of A shares,
referring to those targeted at domestic investors only; 4.66
billion US dollars through the issue of B shares, which are
restricted to overseas buyers; and 10.08 billion US dollars
through the flotation of H shares in Hong Kong, according to the
latest official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from more than 200 enterprises and
intermediary service institutions from both at home and overseas
are attending the seminar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
