<HEADLINE> Arab FMs to Discuss Mideast Peace in Cairo This Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Arab foreign ministers will
hold talks on the Mideast peace process and other vital issues
concerning the Arab nation at the Cairo-based Arab League (AL)
Wednesday, the Middle East News Agency reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat is
scheduled to address the AL Council session to open at foreign
ministers level.
</P>
<P>
His speech will deal with the current Mideast peace dilemma and
the Palestinian issue as both topics are high on the agenda of the
session.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's meeting will be another major Arab bid to press
ahead the stalled Arab-Israeli peace-making since the Council last
convened in the Egyptian capital on March 24.
</P>
<P>
At that time, the foreign ministers urged the Mideast peace
co-sponsors to intensify efforts to get Israel to abide by all
relevant international resolutions and resume talks on all peace
tracks.
</P>
<P>
The March gathering also called for continuing Arab contacts
with the United Nations and world countries to forge a unified
stance enabling Palestine to become a U.N. member. Palestine's
status in the U.N. has been upgraded to a near-state one, in July.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is also likely to study the new developments of the
Lockerbie issue and possibility of fixing the seven-year crisis
over the trial of Libyan suspects over the bombing of an American
plane through a tentative solution at hand.
</P>
<P>
AL Secretary General Esmat Abdel Meguid has played an effective
role in helping Libya and the West to reach a compromise recently.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the issues of setting up an Arab mechanism to settle
inter-Arab differences and the Arab Court of Justice are among the
vital issues to be discussed.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will also discuss the nuclear threat in the Middle
East region and the future of the Afro-Arab cooperation, MENA
added. 
</P>
