<HEADLINE> Manchester United Still Open to Offers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 13 (Xinhua) -- English Premier League club
Manchester United is still open to offers if they can better the
623 milliion pounds BSkyB bid for the club, club chairman Martin
Edwards said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the BBC's Radio 5 Live, Martin Edwards said the
takeover of the club by the media giants was not a 'done deal'.
</P>
<P>
And despite heavy fire from fans opposed to the deal, he said
he wished to stay at the club's helm.
</P>
<P>
He said: "I certainly hope to stay as chairman. I want to and
I have been asked to and it is my intention to do so."
</P>
<P>
Lawyer Tom Usher told the programme that there is still time
for a rival bid to be made.
</P>
<P>
"It is perfectly open for someone to come in and make a rival
bid," said the lawyer.
</P>
<P>
"This is far from being a done deal. The Office of Fair
Trading will look at this takeover and weigh up the volume of
complaints and analyse if it is against the public interest."
</P>
<P>
Mr. Edwards conceded there was a possibility that BSkyB may
lose out on United.
</P>
<P>
"You are honour bound to listen to a bid. You are advised by
your merchant bankers and they will tell you whether to discuss a
deal or not."
</P>
<P>
But Vic Wakeling, head of Sky sports, said: "We do not think
there is a competition problem here."
</P>
<P>
Mr. Edwards was also quizzed about previous bids for the club
by Robert Maxwell and Michael Knighton.
</P>
<P>
"The Maxwell bid never got off the ground and in 1989 when
Michael Knighton approached us we did not then have the money to
rebuild the Stretford End."
</P>
<P>
"We needed to rebuild the stand and I felt that if I refused I
was putting myself above the interests of the fans," said Edwards.
</P>
<P>
