<HEADLINE> Kazakh President Optimistic about Investment Inflow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Kazakh President Nursultan
Nazarbayev said the financial crisis in Southeast Asia and Russia
has not directly affected foreign investors' zest to invest in his
country despite its negative impact on the Kazakh economy.
</P>
<P>
In the first seven months this year, Kazakhstan attracted a
total of 1.6 billion U.S. dollars in foreign investment, which is
expected to continue its growth in the fourth quarter of the year,
reports here said.
</P>
<P>
Political stability is an important precondition for the
attraction of foreign investment, Nazarbayev said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the president said, Kazakhstan places a high premium
on improving its domestic investment environment and has worked
out a series of regulations and premium policies for the benefits
of foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
He said the Foreign Investment Commission under his direction
will convene for the first time in the latter half of
September.
</P>
<P>
By then, representatives from ten big foreign businesses and
banks stationed in Kazakhstan will be invited to attend the
meeting in which they are expected to air their views on a range
of issues related to the Kazakh investment environment to help
improve it.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, Kazakhstan has reportedly absorbed an investment
inflow of 11 billion U.S. dollars, 35 percent of which has gone to
the field of petroleum and natural gas. 
</P>
