<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier on Post-Flood Reconstruction  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji
has said that the reconstruction of flooded areas on the upper and
middle reaches of the Yangtze River should be combined with the
aim of eliminating future flood threats.
</P>
<P>
Zhu, also a member of the Standing Committee of the Political
Bureau of the Communist Party of China (CPC) Central Committee,
made the statement during a study tour of the provinces of Hubei,
Jiangxi, Hunan and Sichuan, and the municipality of Chongqing
September 7-12.
</P>
<P>
The four provinces and municipality, all on the upper or middle
reaches of the Yangtze River, were this summer severely hit by the
worst flooding of China's longest river since 1954.
</P>
<P>
"The most urgent tasks right now are to make sure that the
people displaced by the flood can survive the winter and to
combine the reconstruction of the flood-devastated areas with work
to guard against and prevent future floods," Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, greater efforts must be made to do a good job
in the next three or more months of accomplishing this year's
economic growth target, he said.
</P>
<P>
While the flood-control efforts should be continued as the
floods recede, the focus of work should be shifted to post-flood
reconstruction, the premier said.
</P>
<P>
First of all, he said, "we must take various measures to
rebuild the schools, health-care facilities and residential houses
destroyed by the floods."
</P>
<P>
Efforts must also be made to ensure that the flood-affected
people have enough to eat and wear, have places to live in, and
have ways to prevent and treat diseases, while students can
settle down to study, Zhu added.
</P>
<P>
He underlined that the effort to rapidly restore life and
production in the flood-hit areas should be combined with the aim
to harness the rivers and accomplish the long-term goals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
