<HEADLINE> Clashes Continue Between Palestinians, Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Five Palestinians were
wounded in the West Bank Sunday as the clashes between the
Palestinians and Israeli soldiers entered the third straight day
following the killing of two Palestinians by Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reports said that four teenagers and a
seven-year-old girl were injured by rubber bullets and tear gas
fired by Israeli soldiers near a Jewish settlement southeast of
Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
The clashes erupted when Palestinian students threw rocks at
an Israeli army roadblock, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli soldiers closed a road near another West
Bank town of Ramallah, home to Imad Awadallah and his brother,
who were killed on Thursday night, after a spate of
stone-throwing incidents in the last two days.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of Palestinians and four Israeli soldiers have been
injured in several clashes in the West Bank and Gaza since
Israeli soldiers shot dead Awadallah brothers in Hebron on
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
Israel said the two were leaders of a military wing of
Hamas which was behind two deadly suicide bombings in west
Jerusalem last year killing dozens of Israelis and injured
hundreds of others.
</P>
<P>
Israeli army said the West Bank and Gaza would remain
closed for at least the next few days due to warnings of
planned terror attacks. All Palestinians have been barred from
entering Israel since the army clamped the closure early Friday
morning, but Palestinian goods were allowed in since Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Hamas has vowed to revenge the killing of Awadallah
brothers, threatening to "respond with painful actions." The
Israeli army is said to believe that there are still Hamas
activists capable of carrying out suicide attacks within the
borders of Israel.
</P>
<P>
The tension broke out at a time when U.S. Middle East
envoy Dennis Ross is in the region shuttling between Israel
and the Palestinians in an effort to bridge their gaps over
the long overdue Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Ross, who has held separate talks with Palestinian National
Authority President Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu, traveled to Egypt earlier Sunday to brief
President Hosni Mubarak on the progress of the talks.
</P>
<P>
Israel has failed recently to persuade Cairo to pressure
Arafat to accept its proposals which the Palestinians said were
not in conformity with the U.S. initiative calling for
Israel to hand over an additional 13.1 percent of the West
Bank to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Ross has succeeded in arranging a meeting between Israeli
Cabinet secretary Danny Naveh and senior Palestinian negotiator
Saeb Erekat. The two will meet Sunday night at the residence
of U.S. Ambassador to Israel Edward Walker. 
</P>
</TEXT>
