<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Hopes Clinton's Scandal to Pass Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu hoped on Sunday that U.S. President Bill
Clinton's sex scandal will pass soon.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Israel Radio, Netanyahu said that Clinton
is a friend of Israel, and "he wants what's best for us and we
want what's best for him and the United States."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu stressed that he did not want to interfere in the
internal affairs of the U.S., but his impression "is that the
American society, the democracy and the presidency are very secure
institutions and they will pass the test."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu added that he hopes "this affair will be over soon
and the U.S. will do (what) everyone expects as a great power, to
protect peace and ward off threats to it."
</P>
<P>
The independent counsel Kenneth Starr submitted his report on
the investigation of Clinton last Friday to Congress, which will
decide whether the report will lead to impeachment of the
president.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. Middle East peace envoy Dennis Ross is
continuing his mediation between the Israeli and Palestinian
leaders over the second redeployment of Israeli troops in the
West Bank to unblock the 18-month-old impasse.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is expected to meet Netanyahu and Palestinian National
Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat in the U.S. later this month, in
a bid to hammer out an agreement on the further withdrawal.
</P>
</TEXT>
