<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Win World Women's Volleyball Grand Prix Finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Two-time World Grand Prix
champions Brazil came out the biggest newsmakers as they stunned
the crowd by beating defending champions Russia three sets to
none to win the World Women's Volleyball Grand Prix Finals here
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilians, who had been rated lowly due to their sub-par
performance during the preliminaries of the Grand Prix, downed
Olympic champions Cuba in the semi-finals on Saturday, which
became the biggest upset of this year's tournament.
</P>
<P>
The South Americans downed the Russians 15-11, 15-13, 15-9 in
the finals Sunday afternoon to take their third Grand Prix title.
Brazil won the 1994 and 1996 Finals.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the afternoon, Cuba downed hosts and local crowd
favorites China 3-15, 15-8, 15-9, 15-7 to take the third place.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilians successfully kept their top form they
demonstrated less than 20 hours ago when beating the Cubans.
They pushed the Russians so hard in the finals that the defending
champions made one error after another after losing two sets in a
row. The Brazilian team won the match in straight sets in one
hour and 29 minutes.
</P>
<P>
"We had been well prepared for the match today," said
Brazilian coach Bernardo Rizende. "We blocked and defended very
well and this is the key to our victory," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We knew what we were doing and, as our players were tired
after a long tournament, anything could happen if the match went
longer than three sets," he continued.
</P>
<P>
The head coach said his team would try their best to win the
coming world champonships.
</P>
<P>
With excellent serving and blocking, hosts China took the
opening set 15-3 over Cuba with fairly easy efforts. But a lack
of stamina cost them badly as they lost the three following sets
in about one hour and 20 minutes, after collecting only 24 points.
</P>
<P>
Chinese head coach Lang Ping praised the Cuban side as they
stood calm and collected themselves together and reversed the
tide by winning back the follwoing sets. "Their successful
serving destroyed the attacking chances of our side," she said.
</P>
<P>
Lang said her team will aim at the semi-finals of the coming
world championships. "But we had first to beat such teams as
South Korea, Italy and Croatia. We have a very difficult draw
for the championships," she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
