<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Builds More Schools to Expand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Addis Ababa, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The Addis Ababa regional
administration has announced that new schools will be built with
the old ones renovated in 98/99 fiscal year at a cost of 44.9
million Birr (6.3 million US Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Twenty elementary schools will be built by government funds,
30 elementary schools by aid obtained from Swedish International
Development Agency and 16 others by loans from the World Bank,
according to Biq Ale Seyoum, head of the regional education
bureau.
</P>
<P>
Sunday's "Ethiopian Herald" quoted him as saying that 24
elementary schools will be renovated, expanded and up-graded by
the government, while 1-6 grade schools will be up-graded to 1-8
grade schools with loans from the World bank.
</P>
<P>
Construction of 66 elementary schools which began during the
previous year will be soon completed and able to open educational
opportunities for over 12,000 students, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that educational coverage in the region will be
increased to 50 percent by 2002.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local press reported on Saturday that 25 elementary
schools will be built in Benishangul-Gumuz Region, in
northwestern Ethiopia, with a total cost of nine million Birr
(1.2 million Dollars). The schools are expected to admit 5,000
students and help expand regional educational coverage from the
current 60 percent to 63 percent.
</P>
<P>
In southern Oromia Region, preparations are being made to
build 24 elementary schools with four million Birr (560,000 US
Dollars). Upon completion, they will allow some 5,000 children
get access to education.
</P>
<P>
At present, Ethiopia's educational coverage stands nearly 40
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
