<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Opening-Up On Track, Despite Asian Financial Crisis (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 13 (Xinhua) -- China's pace of opening-up to
the outside world has not slowed down, despite the adverse impact
on the country's economic and social life from the Asian financial
crisis; in fact, it has has expanded in depth and scope.
</P>
<P>
The second China Investment and Trade Fair, held in this port
city in east China's Fujian Province September 8-12, chalked up
2,766 business contracts involving a use of 14.21 billion US
dollars in overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
The success of the fair has fully shown the confidence and
determination of the Chinese government to persevere in the reform
and opening-up drive, increase the use of overseas investment and
reach the economic growth goal.
</P>
<P>
More than 13,000 projects for economic cooperation and
investment offered at the fair aroused great interest among
approximately 7,000 participating overseas business people.
</P>
<P>
While addressing a seminar on China's policies regarding the
use of overseas investment, Shi Guangsheng, minister of foreign
trade and economic cooperation (MOFTEC), announced at the fair
that China would further open competitive industries to investors
from overseas, increase the inflow of overseas investment in the
petrochemical and construction sectors, and open up the service
trade step by step.
</P>
<P>
The reform of the country's financial and telecommunications
sectors will be main subjects for experiments in the next stage of
China's opening-up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980913.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Opening-Up On Track, Despite Asian Financial Crisis (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Liu Mingkang, deputy governor of the People's Bank of China,
said China will allow more foreign financial institutions that
meet the stipulated conditions to set up solely-invested or
jointly-invested ventures, or branch business undertakings on the
Chinese mainland so as to to continue to have an appropriate
growth in the number of foreign financial organizations in China,
and will also let more foreign financial organizations in the
country do business in Chinese currency.
</P>
<P>
China is ready to conduct wide exchanges and detailed research,
and discuss the possibility and forms of cooperation with foreign
financial organizations in the aspect of housing finance.
</P>
<P>
At the fair, China made it clear that it was further improving
its opening-up structure, which is underpinned by by five special
economic zones, open coastal cities, border towns, open cities
along major rivers, and open inland provincial capitals and
counties (cities).
</P>
<P>
In addition to successfully operating special economic zones,
Shanghai's Pudong New Area, the industrial park in Suzhou invested
in by Singapore, and various national economic and technological
development zones, China will actively direct overseas investment
to the central and western areas of the country.
</P>
<P>
China's construction market is vast, and by the end of this
century this sector is expected to chalk up more than 500 billion
yuan (60.4 billion US dollars) in added value.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Vice-Minister of Construction Song Chunhua said that
China will make full use of its various advantages to open its
construction market and increase the use of overseas investment in
this sector.
</P>
<P>
To attract more transnationals to invest in China, the country
will continue opening up the domestic market in a bid to import
advanced foreign technology. Chinese companies will be encouraged
to introduce advanced practical technologies, funds, management
expertise and marketing forms via cooperation with transnationals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980913.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Opening-Up On Track, Despite Asian Financial Crisis (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An official with the State Economic and Trade Commission
reiterated that China will continue to encourage foreign
businesspeople to invest more funds in technical upgrading and
innovations in its existing enterprises, direct foreign investors
to participate in the strategic adjustment of the state economy,
support the use of overseas funds for non-fixed-asset construction
in state enterprises, improve the capital and assets structure of
enterprises, promote mergers and reorganize state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, China has decided to resume exempting tariffs and
value-added taxes from imported equipment needed by overseas
investors who have made investment in industries China wants to
develop.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, all overseas-backed enterprises in China will
enjoy tax rebates in exporting their products -- just as Chinese
companies do -- beginning New Year's Day 1999.
</P>
<P>
In the course of many rounds of cuts, China's average import
tariff rate has fallen to the present 17 percent from 43.2 percent
in 1992. By the year 2000, the country's average import tariff
rate will further be down to about 15 percent or so.
</P>
<P>
MOFTEC sources said China will introduce more overseas funds by
experimenting with more internationally practiced forms of
attracting foreign investment, and allow small state enterprises
and collective enterprises to start joint ventures with overseas
investors, the sale of such enterprises to overseas investors and
the use of overseas investment in China's private enterprises.
</P>
</TEXT>
