<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Economy Picks Up in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 13 (Xinhua) -- China's principal economic
index show an overall rebound in August, according to a
just-released monthly State Statistics Bureau (SSB) report.
</P>
<P>
The report reveals that China generated an industrial added
value of 158.2 billion yuan in August, up 7.9 percent on an annual
basis or 0.3 of a percent point higher than in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
The accumulated industrial added value for the first eight
months totaled 1.2 trillion yuan, representing a 7.8 percent rise
from the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
This was attributed to the impetus of China's massive
infrastructure investment since early this year. Heavy industry
production, especially in the sphere of industrial materials,
witnessed leaps and bounds.
</P>
<P>
The country's industrial sales-output ratio in August reached
97.6 percent, representing the highest rate of the year.
</P>
<P>
The state sector recorded 158.1 billion yuan of fixed-assets
investment during the period, up 26.9 percent over the
corresponding month of last year and 4.1 percentage points higher
than in July. This brought the total for the first eight months to
894.3 billion yuan, up 17.4 percent on a yearly basis.
</P>
<P>
In the first eight months of the year, 513.8 billion yuan of
investment went to infrastructure projects, 176.8 billion yuan was
used as renovation capital and 157.3 billion yuan went into real
estate development.
</P>
<P>
The report also shows that the social retail volume in August
amounted to 231.5 billion yuan-worth, an annual rise of 9.3
percent. Stimulated by flood relief demand, sales of food,
medicines, cooling and heat stroke-preventive commodities became
hot sellers.
</P>
<P>
In August, although the consumer price index was still 1.4
percent lower than the previous year's level, prices for major
items, such as grain, meat and vegetables, inched up a little bit,
compared with the previous month.
</P>
<P>
Foreign trade posted a slight fall in August, with exports
dipping 2.9 percent to 15.6 billion US dollars-worth and imports
edging down 1.7 percent to 10.9 billion dollars-worth. A trade
surplus of 4.7 billion dollars was recorded.
</P>
<P>
The SSB said that in the remaining months of this year China
will still focus on tapping domestic market potential to stimulate
the economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
