<HEADLINE> Taliban Claim Capture of Shiite Opposition Stronghold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The Islamic Taliban militia
Sunday claimed that they had captured the central Afghan city of
Bamyan, forcing the Shiite Hezb-e-Wahdat leaders and fighters to
flee towards mountains.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban forces overran the Bamyan provincial capital at
1:30 p.m. (Afghan local time) without facing any significant
resistance, Taliban's envoy Saeedur Rahman Haqqani told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The militia fighters took control of two airports and seized
four helicopters, 50 tanks and huge quantity of ammunition, he
claimed.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban official said the leadership of the Hezb-e-Wahdat
including its chief Karim Khalili and some Iranian nationals were
evacuated from the city in three Iranian planes Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Citizens in Banyam province are surrendering their arms to the
Taliban forces, he said. adding that all Taliban prisoners in
Bamyan have been released.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Sunday, the Pakistan-based Afghan Islamic Press also
reported the fall of Bamyan to the Taliban. No further details and
independent confirmation are immediately available. 
</P>
</TEXT>
