<HEADLINE> Jordan Condemns Killing of Iranian Diplomats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Foreign Minister
Abdul Ilah al-Khatib on Sunday condemned the killing of nine
Iranian diplomats in Afghanistan, the official Petra news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
In a telegram sent to his Iranian counterpart Kamal Kharrazi,
al-Khatib "denounced the assassination of the Iranian diplomats at
the hands of irresponsible elements in Afghanistan as a crime that
breaches teachings of Islamic Sharia (doctrine), humanitarianism
as well as international principles," the agency said.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of Jordanian government, the foreign minister
expressed condolences on the death of the diplomats.
</P>
<P>
For weeks, Iran had accused the Taliban, Afghanistan's student
militia, of holding 70 Iranians, including 11 diplomats and a
journalist after taking the city of Mazar-e-Sharif in northern
Afghanistan on August 8, but the Taliban had denied any knowledge
of the whereabouts of the diplomats.
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday, the Taliban confirmed it had found the bodies of
nine Iranian diplomats and admitted that they were killed by its
militiamen.
</P>
<P>
Iran has massed a massive force along the border with
Afghanistan for military exercises last week and vowed on Friday
to avenge the killing of these diplomats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
