<HEADLINE> TV Debate Between Australian PM Howard and Beazley </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Australia's two political
heavyweights Prime Minister John Howard and Opposition leader Kim
Beazley clashed over the TV Sunday night as the five-week election
campaign is entering its third week Monday.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister John Howard launched a strong defense of his tax
reforms including a Goods and Services Tax (GST), arguing that the
government would not be able to provide basic services without it.
</P>
<P>
"Every recognized authority on taxation knows that we need to
change our tax system, that otherwise we won't be able to provide
the health services, the police, the roads and the education,
particularly through the states," he said.
</P>
<P>
But Beazley described the GST as desperately unfair and
unsustainable, "it is a tax in Europe which is more often evaded
than it is honored, it is at the heart of their black economy."
</P>
<P>
Using the leaders debate, the first and probably last, Howard
also tried to boast his government's economic competence, while
federal Opposition Leader Beazley argued that the election should
be about the unity of Australians.
</P>
<P>
In his opening address in the debate, Howard said his
government had achieved a budget surplus 12 months ahead of
schedule and brought interest rates to their lowest level in 30
years.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that the government I lead, at a time of difficult
international economic circumstances, is better able to provide
greater strength and greater security for the Australian people,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"The most important question people have got to ask themselves
is whether they wish to go back after only two and a half years to
the Labor Party or whether they're prepared to stick with the
government," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"But there's another reason why we should be returned, and that
is because we have the political courage to take the next
important step to further strengthen the Australian economy, and
that is to give Australia a new and fairer taxation system," he
stated.
</P>
<P>
Howard said the GST plan would boost exports and guarantee the
revenue needed in the future to provide services to the community.
</P>
<P>
But Beazley said Howard inherited high economic growth and high
jobs growth from the Keating Labor government. "What Mr. Howard
has is not a plan for a nation but a plan for a tax - it is a
risky tax," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is a tax on jobs, a tax on consumers, at a point in time
when there are very substantial concerns confronting the
Australian economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
And he said the election campaign needed to be about more than
the economy, and that people needed the security of a decent
public health system.
</P>
<P>
"This election campaign has to be about the unity of our people
- we've lost our way over the last two and a half years," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We've turned against each other rather than to each other. We
now need a government of uniting our people ... confident in their
sense of nationalism as Australians, confident in their future -
and security and opportunity gives them that," he went on.
</P>
<P>
The nationally televised debate lasted one hour from 7:30 to
8:30 PM local time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
