<HEADLINE> Greek Cypriot Pilgrims Visit Northern Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 13 (Xinhua) -- More than 1,000 Greek
Cypriots crossed into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled northern
Cyprus on Sunday for pilgrimage at the monastery of Apostolos
Andreas on the eastern tip of the island.
</P>
<P>
The 1,082 pilgrims, who were of all ages, gathered early
Sunday at Ledra Palace check point in Nicosia, the only way
through which one can enter the northern areas.
</P>
<P>
Strict measures were taken by police to make sure that things
would run smoothly after information came that some
anti-occupation groups against the visit might try to obstruct it.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Pancyprian Anti-occupation Movement had earlier
this week announced their intention to cross into the Turkish
Cypriots-controlled areas, demanding their right to free movement
and free performance of their religious rites.
</P>
<P>
The roads to Ledra Palace check point were blocked by police
and only those whose names were on official lists prepared by the
presidential commissioner for humanitarian affairs were allowed to
pass.
</P>
<P>
The pilgrims, who were arranged by the U.N. Peacekeeping Force
in Cyprus, were transferred in Turkish Cypriot buses to the
monastery, 150 kilometers northeast of Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
It is the third pilgrimage in the past 13 months. More than
1,600 Greek Cypriots have visited the monastery on two occasions
since August last year.
</P>
<P>
The trips were allowed by the Turkish Cypriot side in return
for Turkish Cypriots being allowed to visit the Kokkina enclave in
government-controlled northeastern part of the island and pay
pilgrimage to Hala Tekke Mosque in Larnaca.
</P>
<P>
The exchange of visits was agreed upon by Cypriot President
Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash during
their meetings in Nicosia last year.
</P>
<P>
This east Mediterranean island has been divided since 1974
when Turkey landed its troops and took over the northern third of
the island in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
People in the two sides have been prohibited to cross the
180-kilometer-long U.N.-controlled buffer zone which separates
the island into two parts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
