<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Inflation Rises to Three-Year High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 13 (Xinhua) -- India's annual rate of
inflation had shot up to a three-year high of 8.78 percent for the
week ending on August 29, 1998 on sharp increase in prices of
edible oils, official sources said here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
This is the highest rate of inflation in the country since
1995. The sudden upsurge of prices was mainly on account of
resurgence of price rise in food items, especially in edible oils
following a ban on the use of mustard oil, which has caused dropsy
scare in the capital of New Delhi and other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the capital, many states have banned the use of
mustard oil after it was found to be adulterated. In one week
alone since then prices of imported edible oils have shot up by 24
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
