<HEADLINE> Besenyei Wins First Leg of Aerobatics Grand Prix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Peter Besenyei of Hungary
displayed great music flair and superb aerobatic skills to win
the first leg of the FAI China Cup aerobatics grand prix here on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Besenyei, the inventor of knife-edge skill which is now very
popular in aerobatics, snatched the title with 8.367 points.
</P>
<P>
The lanky 42-year-old Hungarian was followed by Russian
Nikolai Timofeev on 8.357. Viktor Tchmal, also from Russia, came
in third on 8.138.
</P>
<P>
"The pilots' scores are very close today," said chief judge
Quintin Hawthorne. "In this competition, it requires much ability
to interpret the accompanying music and that just comes into
Besenyei's way."
</P>
<P>
Besenyei said music was his hobby. "I like music very much
and when I was six years old, I began to study playing piano,"
said the beaming Hungarian, "It helps a lot when I perform
aerobatics."
</P>
<P>
The next leg of the grand prix will be held in Nanjing, the
capital city of Jiangsu province in east China, which is three
hours' drive from Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The grand prix, which hailed by FAI president Eilif Ness as
the greatest festival of competitive aerobatics ever held, drew
the top 24 finishers of the world championships held last August.
</P>
<P>
The contestants, in the grand prix to be ended on November
2nd, will go on making tour competitions at Jinan, Tianjin,
Shijiazhuang, Zhengzhou, Wuhan and Changsha. 
</P>
</TEXT>
