<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Kenya's Economic Growth Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The decline in Kenya's
economic growth that started in 1997 continued into May, 1998,
the central bank says in its September issue of the Monthly
Economic Review.
</P>
<P>
Real gross domestic product (GDP) expanded by 1.6 percent in
the year to May, compared with 2.3 percent in 1997 and 1.9
percent in the year to March, 1998. The latest figure is also far
below the country's growth potential, the bank says.
</P>
<P>
The bank warns that the weak economic performance is expected
to persist into the remaining part of 1998 and early 1999 unless
urgent measures focusing on cutting government's domestic debt
are implemented.
</P>
<P>
The government should make broader policy reforms for
enhancing efficiency, improving competitiveness and increasing
capacity utilization in all economic sectors so as to reverse the
general decline of the economy, the central bank urges.
</P>
<P>
The bank says the continuous weak economic growth arises from
the following economic and financial factors:
</P>
<P>
-- The crowding out of the private sector by the government in
the investable funds market which divert productive resources
from the more efficient private sector to public sector;
</P>
<P>
-- The lack of working capital and reduced local investments
caused by the high costs of domestic funds;
</P>
<P>
-- The decline in foreign investment caused by the low
investor confidence; 7
</P>
<P>
-- The dilapidated infrastructure, particularly roads;
</P>
<P>
-- insecurity and the on-and-off labor unrest which
encouraged potential investors to adopt the wait-and-see strategy
in decision making.
</P>
<P>
From May 1997 to May 1998, agricultural output was estimated
to have expanded by only 0.6 percent compared with 1.2 percent in
1997, according to the review.
</P>
<P>
The weak performance was reportedly caused by the adverse
weather, the rising costs of farm inputs and the relative low
returns that continue to accrue from agricultural activities.
</P>
<P>
The cumulative output of coffee fell by 47 percent in the
year to May, compared to the decline of 22.0 percent in the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
The value of coffee exported, in the first four months of
this year, also dropped by 35.7 percent to 4.5 billion Shillings
(75.63 million U.S. Dollars) from seven billion Shillings (117.6
million Dollars) in the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Horticulture exports declined by 9.4 percent in the year to
May, 1998, compared with the 2.1 percent growth in the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
Sisal yield went down by 21.2 percent in the year to May,
1998 compared with the decline of 11.4 percent in the previous
period.
</P>
<P>
Tea production and exports, however, continued to increase
steadily, partkcularly in the first five months of this year. Tea
output shot up by 27.2 and 25.6 percent in the year to April and
the year to May respectively.
</P>
<P>
The hike in tea production was because of favorable
international price and the El Nino-related rains that boosted
output in early 1998, said the central bank in the review.
</P>
<P>
Partly as a result from the competition of cheaper imports,
manufactural industry in Kenya slowed down further to 1.4 percent
in the year to May, 1998 from 1.9 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The depression was also caused by the high costs of domestic
funds which limit access to working capital, as well as the poor
state of infrastructure such as roads, ports, power supply,
telephones and water supply.
</P>
<P>
However, the bank predicted that a recovery in the
manufacturing will begin in early 1999 as more affordable credit
becomes available to the sector.
</P>
<P>
The expansion of the Common Market for Eastern and Southern
Africa (COMESA) and the East African Cooperation is also expected
to lead to improvement in the sector, the bank says.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, growth in trade, restaurants and hotels estimated
to have declined to 3.2 percent in the year to May, 1998 from 3.9
percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, performance in transport, storage and
communication fell to 1.4 percent from 1.8 percent, due to poor
infrastructure, particularly roads. 
</P>
</TEXT>
