<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Irish PM Praises China's Role in Regional Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Irish Prime Minister Bertie
Ahern praised China's role in the Asian financial crisis, saying
"its decision not to devalue its currency represents a very
significant contribution to the whole Asian region and indeed the
global economy."
</P>
<P>
"The real strength of China is demonstrated by its stablizing
role in the region where there is so much financial volatility,"
Ahern said in an interview with Xinhua before he visits China.
</P>
<P>
On his five-day official visit to China starting Monday, the
first by an Irish Prime Minister, Ahern said it is "extremely
important for me personally and for Ireland."
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also expressed his confidence that the visit
will serve to consolidate the "already good bilateral relations"
and "lay the foundations for even closer relations in the future"
between Ireland and China, which he noted have enjoyed increasing
contact in political, economic and social spheres in recent times.
</P>
<P>
China and Ireland, both with rich histories and diverse
cultures, share the same goals of seeking greater prosperity for
their peoples, said the prime minister, adding that he expected
the visit to "allow us to achieve greater understanding of each
other."
</P>
<P>
On what he called excellent economic ties, Ahern said that
"given Ireland's industrial and technical strengths and
competitiveness in world markets, and given the active interest of
Irish companies in doing business in China, I believe that there
is substantial scope for expanding our trade partnership,
particularly in the high technology sectors, in electronics,
telecommunications, chemicals, machinery and other areas."
</P>
<P>
Ireland greatly welcomes China's intention to become a member
of the World Trade Organization and hopes that the current
negotiations will be speedily concluded on acceptable terms to all
so that China can take its rightful place in the world trade
community and share to the full in its economic benefits, Ahern
said.
</P>
<P>
The Irish prime minister also expressed satisfaction with the
progress of the China-European Union (EU) relations in different
fields.
</P>
<P>
Ireland is very pleased with the outcome of the EU-China summit
in this past April, and the ASEM (Asia-Europe Meeting) process
will continue to promote China's ties with the EU.
</P>
<P>
Talking about China's role on the international arena, Ahern
said that "China's position at the United Nations as one of the
five permanent members of the Security Council (of the United
Nations) puts it at the forefront of international political
developments."
</P>
<P>
"We are heartened by the responsible role which has been played
by China on many international issues at the United Nations," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
