<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Determined to Maintain Steady Supply of Food </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government is
determined to maintain steady supply of food to the people in any
circumstances as it has adequate food grains to meet the
post-flood demand in the country, said an official handout
reaching here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The government has decided to import one million tons of
additional food on commercial basis to increase its food reserves,
it said, adding that arrangements for importing 0.6 million tons
of rice and wheat had already been finalized.
</P>
<P>
Arrangements for importing the remaining 0.4 million tons of
foodstuff are now under process.
</P>
<P>
At least 218,000 tons of wheat purchased on commercial basis
will reach Chittagong port between the last week of this month and
the middle of the next month, the handout said.
</P>
<P>
Owing to the devastating flood, which has lasted for over two
months and destroyed large areas of crops in the country, the
total loss in grain output might increase to the level of two
million tons or more, according to an estimate made recently by a
United Nations disaster management team.
</P>
<P>
The government has already made appeal to the donor countries
and international agencies for 1.38 million tons of food grains to
avoid any famine after the flood. 
</P>
</TEXT>
