<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0830 GMT, September 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA -- NATO started a military maneuver in Macedonia
Saturday to show its military strength, news reports from
Macedonia's capital Skopje said.
</P>
<P>
The eight-day exercise, coded Best Cooperative Effort 98, aims
at intervention in conflicts under the U.N. resolutions. As many
as 1,500 soldiers from 13 NATO members including the United State
and 13 NATO countries of peaceful partnership including Albania
take part in the three-stage maneuver. (NATO-Military Exercise)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SARAJEVO -- Sarajevo residents lined up in front of the polling
stations early Saturday morning as Bosnia's second general
election started across the country.
</P>
<P>
The election, going on over the weekend, is being held under
the 1995 Dayton peace accord which ended the three-and-a-half-year
Bosnian war and divided the former Yugoslav republic into two
ethnically-based entities -- the Serb republic and the
Muslim-Croat federation. More than 2.7 million have registered to
elect Bosnia's three-member state presidency, state parliament
deputies and the two entities' assemblies as well as the president
of the Serb entity. (Bosnia-Elections)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The 14-day Northwest Airline pilots strike ended
Saturday after leaders of the pilots union ratified a four-year
contract with the fourth largest airlines in the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Northwest pilots may now return to work," said Steve Zoller,
chairman of the 17-member pilots' executive council, which
ratified the tentative agreement reached with the company on
Thursday. According to the agreement, the pilots will have a 12
percent pay increase over the four years under the new contract.
(US-Pilots-Strike)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- Azem Hajdari, vice chairman of Albania's Democratic
Party and chairman of the Parliamental Defense Commission, was
gunned down in front of his party's head office on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
Albania's SHIJAK television station reported that Hajdari was
shot dead by bullets fired from a police car. No one has claimed
responsibility for the killing, and no suspect has been found so
far. Speaking on television, Albanian party leaders condemned the
killing and voiced worries that it would heighten the tensions in
the country. (Albania-Assassination) 
</P>
</TEXT>
