<HEADLINE> Philippines Wages War Against Street Children Syndicates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada has ordered a fresh crackdown on syndicates forcing
children to beg in the streets or peddle illegal drugs, Press
Undersecretary Lcasiano Gutierrez said here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Gutierrez said the president mounted the campaign after
receiving reports that these children were being held captive and
coerced to pose as beggars by well-entrenched syndicates which
squeeze them of their earnings every night.
</P>
<P>
The worse, some drug rings have allegedly been using these
children as couriers of their illegal trade, he added.
</P>
<P>
The president, Gutierrez said, has instructed the police and
local government officials to go hard on these syndicates, saying
there will be no sacred cows in this campaign.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching the Office of the President said these
syndicates were being protected by some influential groups and
quartered in four safe houses in Metro Manila.
</P>
<P>
Estrada tapped the Department of Social Welfare and Development
as the lead agency in overseeing the campaign to help the
resettlement and rehabilitation of the street children who number
more than 75,000 in the capital region alone.
</P>
<P>
Gutierrez said President Estrada described the plight of the
kids as "a deep social wound" which demands serious attention from
the government and the private sector alike.
</P>
<P>
"The president said the government will be relentless against
these syndicates because by destroying the future of these
children, they are undermining the very future of our country,"
Gutierrez said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
