<DOCNO> XIE19980913.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Leads Commonwealth Games Medals Table </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Australia's shooters
grabbed two gold medals to put the country on the top of the
medals standings on the second day of the Commonwealth Games
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Australia's Carolyn Quigley and Kim Frazier retained their r
ifle prone pairs title and Christine Trefry and Annette Woodward
won the women's sport pistol pairs in Sunday's shooting
competition.
</P>
<P>
Also on Sunday, Cara Honeychurch and Maxim Nable took the
tenpin bowling women's pairs and that, for the moment, took A
ustralia ahead of England in the all-time Commonwealth Games
medal table with seven gold, five silver and four bronze medals.
</P>
<P>
England took four golds, one silver and two bronzes with Chris
Hector and Nigel Wallace winning the men's pairs air rifle and N
ick Baxter and Michael Gault taking the men's pairs free pistol
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
It was bad for the Australian team for its elite swimmer
Michael Klim hitting a slump in form.
</P>
<P>
The 21-year-old qualified for 100 meters butterfly final -- an
event in which he holds the world title and world record -- with
only the fifth fastest heats time.
</P>
<P>
He also struggled in Saturday's 200m freestyle heats and was
well beaten by schoolboy Ian Thorpe in the final.
</P>
<P>
Klim won the butterfly world title in January with the best
time of the year, 52.25sec.
</P>
<P>
Aussie swimming legend Kieron Perkins only returned to
training Sunday after being struck down by illness.
</P>
<P>
Canada's Lyn Bessette won the women's 192-kelometer cycling
road race title on Sunday after tragedy struck Anna Wilson.
</P>
<P>
The 26-year-old Wilson, who was aiming to preserve Australia's
unbeaten reign in the road race, looked to have the gold medal
sewn up until her foot slipped off the pedal 500 meters from the
finish.
</P>
<P>
Bessette, who converted middle distance running to take up
cycling two years ago, swept past her to Canadia's second golds
at the current Games.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian hosts had another stunning day, taking two more
silver medals through Lai Kin Ngoh and Shalin Zulkifli in the
women's tenpin bowling and Mutalib Abdul Razak and Mohd Emran
Zakaria in the men's pairs air rifle.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia had collected three silver and one bronze medals,
ahead of New Zealand (0-2-0) and Scotland (0-0-2). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
