<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPP Supporters Holds Large-Scale Demonstrators in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, September 13 (Xinhua) -- About 20,000 supporters of
the Cambodian People's Party (CPP) demonstrated Sunday morning,
and Chea Sim, CPP president and president of the National
Assembly, urged all parties to solve disputes through dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The CPP supporters, most of them from provinces of Kandal,
Takeo and Kompong Speu, gathered at the Olympic Stadium and were
protected by the fully-armed military police.
</P>
<P>
While marching through city streets at about 9:30 (local time),
the demonstrators, many of whom carried sticks and guns, shouted
against opposition leaders Sam Rainsy and Prince Norodom
Ranariddh, demanding they accept the results of the July 26
election and urging Ranariddh to join new Assembly session.
</P>
<P>
The police blocked the main streets. No clashes were reported.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chea Sim made a statement Sunday on behalf of the
National Assembly, calling for all political parties to stop
holding rival demonstrations and heed to the call of King Norodom
Sihanouk to avoid further bloodshed clashes.
</P>
<P>
He also urged all Cambodian politicians, especially the three
major parties, to resolve their disputes through dialogues, which
will help the convening of the National Assembly session and the
formation of a new government.
</P>
<P>
The opposition Funcinpec party and Sam Rainsy Party (SRP) have
agreed Saturday to cancel its Sunday-planned mass rally of 20,000
supporters, after they are requested by the government not to hold
further rally to avoid clashes.
</P>
<P>
"In order to ease the tension of bloodshed in the capital, we
have decided to postpone our mass demonstration tomorrow," Prince
Ranariddh, president of Funcinpec Party, said Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980913.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reform of State-owned Firms Pays Off in Liaoning Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Liaoning Province, a leading
heavy industry center in northeast China, has made breakthroughs
in transforming key state-owned firms, technological upgrading
with foreign funds and boosting development of non-governmental
businesses, a provincial official said today.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning has more than 900 large- and medium-size state-owned
enterprises, accounting for one-tenth of the national total. Their
combined fixed assets exceeded 500 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this year, the provincial government
experimented with reforms of ownership in 200 designated large-
and medium-size state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
It has also formed 38 inter-regional and cross-trade enterprise
groups with the largest one, Huajin Chemical Group, having total
assets exceeding 10 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The province has adopted more flexible measures on the
management of smaller firms. Through the end of June, 45 percent
of firms at the municipal level and 60 percent of businesses at
the county or district levels have introduced joint venture or
joint stock systems. Some poorly managed ones have gone bankrupt
or been merged with others.
</P>
<P>
To date, the province has absorbed 3 billion U.S. dollars from
abroad to upgrade 2,200 state-owned enterprises. More than
one-fifth of the top 500 companies in the world are cooperating
with Liaoning in industrial upgrading. About 60 percent of
equipment imported from abroad is close to the highest level in
the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
In the first seven months of this year, 41 of 60 key state
firms built 161 joint ventures with overseas counterparts. The 60
firms are expected to use at least 600 million U.S. dollars in
each of the next few years.
</P>
<P>
A non-government economic commission has been set up in
Shenyang, the provincial capital, to boost the development of
individual or collective firms.
</P>
<P>
The government urged the sector to raise its output value at an
annual rate of 20 percent to reach 70 billion yuan by 2002.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
