<DOCNO> XIE19980913.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Loggers Practice Afforestation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Devastating summer floods in
the Yangtze River Valley have claimed the lives of thousands of
people and caused losses of massive property and have prompted the
Chinese government and people to unveil a massive afforestation
program in related areas.
</P>
<P>
The ban on logging in natural forests in the upper reaches of
the Yangtze have prompted 45,000 lumberjacks in southwest
China's Sichuan Province to abandon the tools of their trade and
pledge to cover the region with trees by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
"We never dreamed our work could produce such catastrophic
consequences," said Shou Cezheng, a lumberjack working for the
forest bureau in Puwei County. Flood waters inundated the home of
Shou's parents-in-law in Jianli County, Hubei Province, one of the
hardest hit regions in the middle reaches of the river.
</P>
<P>
"We must do our best to protect the ecological environment,"
said Shou, who worked as a lumberjack in the deep mountains for
over 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Heavy deforestation has been cited as the major causes of this
year's heavy flooding. Loggers have witnessed a sharp decline in
ancient forests and many have expressed a sense of guilt when
felling trees.
</P>
<P>
Chinese citizens have gradually become aware of the importance
of protecting natural resources and the environment, and the
country has paid a heavy price for the past inattention, said Peng
Huang, deputy director of the Sichuan Forestry Department.
</P>
<P>
"However, related costs and pain will not have been shouldered
in vain, but instead will stimulate us to work harder to rebuild
the nation's forests," said Peng.
</P>
<P>
He said the province plans to plant 140,000 hectares of trees
annually between now and the year 2,010, in addition to carefully
protecting existing forests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
