<HEADLINE> Prolonged Deluge Relaxes in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The two-month-long deluge
across Bangladesh has relaxed its grips as the waters from most
rivers began to recede, except along the coastal belt, media
reports said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
However, the situation would continue to deteriorate in
Chandpur district, 64 kilometers southeast of here, due to
abnormal tidal waves in the Bay of Bengal, despite fall of all the
rivers in the coming hours, the Flood Forecasting and Warning
Center (FFWC) cautioned Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The flood situation along the Brahmaputra-Jamuna and Padma
rivers would also continue to improve in the coming hours, the
FFWC added.
</P>
<P>
In the midst of continued crushing down of water, the rivers in
the north and middle parts of the country started receding though
significant rainfall had been recorded in the upper catchment in
the last 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
"Rainfall is no matter now," said an expert at the Water
Development Board, adding that the water level would go down
"rapidly" in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
The flood situation in the central parts of the country would
continue to improve while around the capital city of Dhaka the
situation might also show slight improvements, the EEWC predicted.
Major rivers, including the Buriganga and the Lakhaya around
Dhaka, displayed downtrend, and the Brahmaputra-Jamuna and the
Padma recorded further fall at all points, the FFWC added.
</P>
</TEXT>
