<HEADLINE> NZ Actively Preparing for Next Year's APEC Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 13 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Minister of
Foreign Affairs and Trade Don McKinnon said here Sunday that the
New Zealand government's planning and preparation for the
Leaders' Meeting of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC)
in Auckland was "well advanced", though it was still 12 months
away.
</P>
<P>
He said in a press release that the APEC meeting will be "the
biggest event ever to be hosted by New Zealand."
</P>
<P>
McKinnon said that late last year the New Zealand government
established the APEC Task Force and the Task Force groups have
been working for some time, examining logistical issues such as
traffic, security, accommodation and airport requirements. The
Task Force will soon have about 50 senior staff, he said.
</P>
<P>
In the press release, McKinnon released the schedule for his
country's hosting of the APEC series of meetings. According to the
 schedule, the Leaders' Meeting of the APEC will be held on
September 12 and 13 in Auckland. Before the leaders' meeting, more
than 10 related meetings for preparing for the leaders' meeting
are scheduled to be organized in Wellington, Auckland,
Christchurch and Rotorua next year.
</P>
<P>
"It will be an exciting and challenging year of meetings for
New Zealand to host," McKinnon said, adding that these meetings
will address "some of the fundamental issues at the heart of the
region's current economic problems".
</P>
<P>
Most members "are keen to continue towards APEC's goal of free
and open trade and investment in the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
McKinnon disclosed that some 11,000 people are expected to
attend the series of APEC 1999 meetings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
