<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Biomedical Industry No. 2 Employer in California: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The biomedical Industry
has become a major employer in California, the United States,
according to a survey released this week.
</P>
<P>
Last year, health care technology businesses ranked second in
employment in the U.S. West Coast state, surpassing the
traditional big employers of motion pictures and aerospace and
trailing only the electronic industry.
</P>
<P>
About 210,000 workers were employed by health care technology
firms in 1997, up 40,000 over the previous year, according to the
survey conducted by the California Healthcare Institute (CHI).
</P>
<P>
The category encompasses biotech, pharmaceuticals, medical
devices and medical diagnostics.
</P>
<P>
In Silicon Valley, 29,000 people are employed in health care
technology careers at 322 companies. Another 3,200 local workers
are engaged in biomedical research and development at the Valley's
Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
San Francisco and San Diego, in the north and south of the
state respectively, are other centers of the industry.
</P>
<P>
CHI said that California reigns in health care technologies
because it has complex and delicately balanced economic
"microclimate" for biotech, which is comprised of academic
scientists, enterprises, capital, investors and the physical place.
</P>
<P>
The industry offers high-paying, knowledge-intensive jobs for
Californians, the CHI study said.
</P>
<P>
The survey found that two-thirds of health technology employees
in Silicon Valley work on medical device and diagnostic projects;
the rest focuses on biotech and pharmaceutical research. They
earn an average salary of 70,000 U.S. dollars -- the highest wage
for the industry of any region in California.
</P>
<P>
With its unique concentration of university research, high-tech
talent and venture capital experience, Silicon Valley has become
the global leader in combining innovative information technology
with breakthroughs in the life science, according to CHI.
</P>
<P>
Such combinations have launched whole new industry sectors,
like the marriage of DNA sequencing and a computer chip technology
called bioinformatics.
</P>
<P>
The biotech industry is growing about two percent a year, no
faster than the overall California economy. But CHI said it
offers a much higher-value product than many other major
industries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980913.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
