<HEADLINE> Bad Weather Forces Mexico to Import More Grains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The Mexican government
will have to import 17 million tons of grains this year, since a
low-than-expected harvest is expected because of the bad weather.
</P>
<P>
Federico Ovalle, chairman of the Permanent Agrarian Congress,
said that floods have damaged lands in the southern states of
Chiapas, Guerrero, Michoacan and Guanajuato.
</P>
<P>
He said rice, corn, beans and lentils will have to be imported
to guarantee the Mexicans sufficient food supply.
</P>
<P>
Ovalle said the Mexican government imports more than five
million tons of agricultural products every year, but this year
the imports will be increased. 
</P>
