<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Northwest Airline Pilots End Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The 14-day Northwest
Airline pilots strike ended Saturday after leaders of the pilots
union ratified a four-year contract with the fourth largest
airlines in the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Northwest pilots may now return to work," said Steve Zoller,
chairman of the 17-member pilots' executive council, which
ratified the tentative agreement reached with the company on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, the pilots will have a 12 percent
pay increase over the four years under the new contract.
</P>
<P>
The pilots had asked for 14 percent increase over three years
while the airline had agreed on a hike of 9 percent over four
years. The dispute triggered the 6,200-pilot strike on August 29.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the salary increase, pilots won a phasing out of
a two-tier wage scale that pays new hires at a lower rate, Zoller
said. They also received stock options and profit sharing, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The strike forced the airline to cancel all its 1,700 daily
flights and temporarily lay off some 30,000 employees. It also
caused the industry a loss of more than 300 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
With the approval of the agreement, Northwest immediately began
to call the laid-off employees back to work.
</P>
<P>
Company officials said it should have one-fourth of its
schedule in operation by Wednesday. The airline expects to be at
full speed by September 21. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
