<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnia's Second General Election Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Sarajevo residents lined up
in front of the polling stations early Saturday morning as Bosnia's
second general election started across the country.
</P>
<P>
The election, going on over the weekend, is being held under
the 1995 Dayton peace accord which ended the three-and-a-half-year
Bosnian war and divided the former Yugoslav republic into two
ethnically-based entities -- the Serb republic and the
Muslim-Croat federation.
</P>
<P>
More than 2.7 million have registered to elect Bosnia's
three-member state presidency, state parliament deputies and the
two entities' assemblies as well as the president of the Serb
entity.
</P>
<P>
As many as 83 parties, coalitions and independent candidates
are contesting in the election, with 12 candidates from 16 parties
representing the Muslims, Croats and Serbs running for the the
three-member state presidency alone.
</P>
<P>
No violent incidents have been reported so far although
balloting process was delayed in dozens of the 2,650 stations due
to computer problems.
</P>
<P>
The prevailing calm and order is seen largely as a result of
the heavy international supervision. Also the presence of the
multinational Stabilization Force of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO), and over 3,000 supervisors from the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
International figures now in Bosnia include NATO
Secretary-General Javier Solana, NATO's Supreme Allied Commander
Wesley Clark, International High Representative to Bosnia Carlos
Westendorp and United Nations Special Envoy Elisabeth Rehn.
</P>
<P>
The international community is cherishing big hopes for the
election to produce new Bosnian leaders who can faithfully
implement the Dayton accord and ensure a smooth post-war
reconstruction and refugees repatriation, while Bosnians are
looking forward to a future of peace and stability. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
