<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dini: Reform Italy's Foreign Aid Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister
Lamberto Dini on Saturday urged for reforms in Italian foreign aid
policies which were formulated back in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
"What needs to be developed are the mechanisms for coordination
and consultation to broaden Italy's international cooperation,"
Dini said, "However, the mechanisms must also ensure that foreign
aid follows a common plan."
</P>
<P>
More private capital has been allowed to flow to the developing
countries since the end of the Cold War, Dini added, so many
governments doubt whether governmental foreign aid should exist.
</P>
<P>
However the Italian government presented to the parliament a
foreign aid bill last December, asking to increase foreign aid
volume from 0.28 percent of the national budget to 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
"With the reform of foreign aid policy," Dini explained, "we
want to streamline the ministry's structures, and dedicate our
energies to negotiation with the recipient nations."
</P>
<P>
Dini added that his ministry would also set up an agency to
speed up the aid deliver. "This is the most crucial point of our
activities today," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
