<HEADLINE> Italian Police Found Gold in Licio Gelli's Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Italian police on Saturday found
170 kilograms of gold in the residence of Licio Gelli, former head
of the once powerful and secret organization P2 Lodge.
</P>
<P>
The gold was found hidden in flower pots in the garden of
Gelli's Tuscan mansion.
</P>
<P>
The search was ordered by Rome prosecutors investigating
charges of usury against Gelli, who has also been sentenced to 12
years in prison for fraud connected to the 1982 collapse of the
Banco Ambrosiano.
</P>
<P>
Gelli, 79, who escaped to France in May when he was sentenced
for the Banco Ambrosiano case, was arrested two days ago in Nice.
</P>
<P>
As head of the P2 Lodge until its discovery in 1981, Gelli
managed a network of figures in the Italian government, military
and probably financial circles in covert anti-communist
activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
