<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Minister: No Need to Revise Draft 1999 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The Italian government sees no
need to revise its draft 1999 budget despite less optimistic
projections for the country's gross domestic production (GDP),
Italian Treasury Minister Carlo Azeglio Ciampi said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The government forecasts an increase of 2.5 percent in GDP this
year, but industrialists and several independent research
institutes are saying that nothing more than 2 percent can be
expected.
</P>
<P>
"A difference of a few tenths of a decimal point does not
automatically mean there will be consequences" for the budget,
Ciampi said.
</P>
<P>
Analysts differ on how much the Russian and Asian crises will
affect Italy, although most agree the impact will be slight.
</P>
<P>
According to Foreign Trade Minister Augusto Fantozzi, Italy is
relatively insulated from the Asian crisis because only 7 percent
of its exports go to China, Japan and Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
The risk from Russia is also "limited" in his view because
export earnings from that country account for as little as 1.7
percent of Italy's GDP.
</P>
<P>
Whatever the effects on GDP, Ciampi argued that any shortfall
in funds entering state coffers would be offset by other factors.
</P>
<P>
He pointed in particular to savings from lower interest rates
on government bonds.
</P>
<P>
In working out the 1999 budget, the government calculated its
interest rate bill on the basis of a 4.5-percent rate on 12-month
bonds. At the last treasury auction, however, rates were down to
4.06 percent.
</P>
<P>
The budget, which must be completed by September 30, is
expected to improve the country's finances by 13.5 trillion lire
(7.7 billion U.S. dollars). The Treasury is aiming at savings of
about 9.5 trillion from cuts and new revenue of about 4 trillion,
mostly from a tax amnesty.
</P>
<P>
There will be no new taxes in the package. After years of
budgetary belt-tightening, Italy's tax burden has risen to become
one of the highest in Europe and employers charge that this is
holding back the economy.
</P>
<P>
At a convention in Bari, Prime Minister Romano Prodi said that
the 1999 budget would launch attempts to reduce taxes paid by
companies on labor and thus free up cash for investment.
</P>
<P>
"With this budget we will begin a long-term manoeuvre to reduce
the fiscal element of labor costs," he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Italy's overall tax burden, Prodi said the
government aims to reduce it thanks to extra revenue resulting
from stricter checks on evasion.
</P>
<P>
The budget would also contain measures aimed at alleviating the
worst cases of poverty, which is a "partly distorted welfare
system ignored," he said.
</P>
<P>
These would be the first steps in a "comprehensive revision of
the welfare system" which parliament will begin debating in
January, Prodi added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
