<HEADLINE> Thai Gov't-Owned Bank to Issue New Shares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Agriculture and
Agricultural Cooperatives of Thailand will issue shares worth 1.5
billion baht (37.5 million U.S. dollars) next month to boost
capital, the Bangkok Post newspaper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Quoting Ennoo Suesuwan, executive vice-president of the bank,
the newspaper said the shares sold to the public will be an
instrument for the bank to increase its lending capability, in
addition to capitalization efforts by the government.
</P>
<P>
The shares will be sold in packages of one ordinary share and
four preferred shares, which can be sold back to the bank after
five years.
</P>
<P>
Ordinary shares will offer a dividend of 2-4 percent while the
preferred shares carry a return equivalent to the going interest
for bank fixed deposit account, or 10-11 percent.
</P>
<P>
The bank choose to issue new shares instead of bonds to boost
its capital because the ongoing interest for bonds is now as high
as 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
The bank has a foundation from which funds can be drawn should
any of the buyers want to resell shares before or at the end of
the five-year period.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry plans to inject some 10 billion baht (250
million dollars) from its sale of global bonds to help increase
the bank's capital but the project has been delayed because of the
delay in the sale of the bonds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
