<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia, Bulgaria Congratulate Primakov for Premiership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia and Bulgaria
Saturday congratulated Yevgeny Primakov for his appointment as
Russia's new prime minister amid the political and economic crises
in Russia.
</P>
<P>
In a congratulatory message to Primakov, Yugoslav Prime
Minister Momir Bulatovic said that he believes the close
traditional friendship and the mutually beneficiary cooperation
between the two countries will continue to develop smoothly.
</P>
<P>
Such development of friendship and cooperation between the two
countries will be conducive to the maintenance of world peace and
to the definition of relations of equity among sovereign states in
the international community, Bulatovic said.
</P>
<P>
Bulgarian Prime Minister Ivan Kostov also sent a congratulatory
message to Primakov Saturday, saying he hopes Primokov would
continue to implement the policy of reform and take resolute
measures to ease the economic crisis in the country.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Bulgarian Minister of Foreign Affairs Nadezhda
Mikhailova said Primakov is a reformist who has the ability to
unite the political forces in Russia and the whole society of the
country, win support from the international community and lead
Russia out of the crises.
</P>
<P>
In Budapest, Hungarian Foreign Minister Martonyi Janos said
Saturday the Hungarian government welcomes Russia's choice and
believes the formation of a new government in Russia will lead to
stability in the country.
</P>
<P>
He added Primokov's familiarity with international affairs
would certainly help Russia get out of the current crises in the
interest of Russia and the whole world.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin named Primakov, 68, as
premier's nominee on Thursday after the State Duma rejected Viktor
Chernomyrdin as candidate for prime minister twice. Russian State
Duma on Friday endorsed Primakov's nomination as prime minister by
an overwhelmingly majority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
