<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Door Opens Wider to Private Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Reconstruction in China's
flooded areas will offer unprecedented investment opportunities to
private capital and foreign investors, "Business Weekly" reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Badly damaged firms that caused serious pollution, relied on
out-of-date technology or showed no sign of making profits before
the floods will be shut down or allowed to die a "natural death,"
said the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Private capital is expected to flow into the areas where the
closure of such plants creates fresh investment potential and room
for development.
</P>
<P>
A principle established by the State Economic and Trade
Commission (SETC) stipulates that reconstruction in flooded areas
should not simply copy the pre-flood situation. For years, many
state enterprises have been expected to have their ownership
structure altered.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, SETC is engaged in discussions with
other ministries on new policies to encourage structural
adjustment of industries and technical upgrading in the
flood-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
Some building materials and construction companies in Beijing
have rushed to Hunan and Hubei provinces to grab orders and
contracts.
</P>
<P>
As the floods recede, local officials are talking about
restarting credit programs for fledgling private enterprises.
Regional authorities that have made persistent efforts to foster
non-public owership seem well aware that this is an ideal moment
to usher in more private capital to restructure old-fashioned
economic structures.
</P>
<P>
A new wave of bankruptcies, mergers and acquisitions is likely
to emerge in view of cheaper labor, lower land-use costs, and
lower prices for property rights of companies affected by the
floods.
</P>
<P>
Fan Gang, director of the National Economic Research Institute,
said the flooding was "well timed" for the government to phase out
loss-making enterprises.
</P>
<P>
To attract more private funds and overseas investment, other
economic specialists also suggested measures such as giving
preferential taxation treatment, favorable loan interest rates to
relatively long-term and low-return infrastructure projects, and
the establishment of a bail-out risk fund for banks lending money
to investors.
</P>
<P>
Information from SETC said that state-allocated funds for
reconstruction will bring up an extra investment of 300 billion
yuan to the flood-hit areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
