<HEADLINE> Thailand Develops Software to Erase Child Porn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 13 (Xinhua) -- A Bangkok-based
non-governmental organization has successfully developed an
anti-virus software with a German firm to block child pornography
on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The software is capable of identifying all files that contain
child pornography sent on the Internet and also erasing similar
files from computers, the Bangkok Post reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted foreign ministry spokesman Kobsak Chutikul as
saying that the organization, End Child Prostitution, Pornography
and Trafficking of Children (ECPAT), had begun distributing the
software, with the cooperation of Thai Interpol.
</P>
<P>
ECPAT has been persuading Internet service providers to use the
software and will encourage general Internet users to install it
in their computers, Kobsak said.
</P>
<P>
The spread of pornographic materials on the Internet prompted
the United Nations to hold a meeting in Stockholm in 1996 and sign
a declaration against child pornography.
</P>
<P>
ECPAT has closely monitored the situation ever since, Kobsak
said.
</P>
<P>
UN figures show that there are now about 650,000 prostitutes
worldwide below 16 years of age. 
</P>
</TEXT>
