<HEADLINE> Castro Meets Former Heavyweight Champ Muhammad Ali </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Cuban President Fidel Castro
has met former heavyweight World champion Muhammad Ali and a
United States delegation which arrived in Cuba to deliver a
donation of medicines for the island.
</P>
<P>
The official daily Granma called "lively" Saturday the
meeting, held Friday afternoon, attended by members of the Fund
for Development and Education, and the Organization for
Development, both U.S. non-governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
Castro said in his conversation with the visitors, that in the
middle of the U.S. trade embargo against the island, the donation
of medical supplies of American citizens is "a great moral
gesture," said the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Bon Schawartz, director of the Fund For Development and
Education, explained to the President the development for four
years of the projects of assistance to several Cuban medical
institutions, for which the donations so far amount to some 20
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Muhammad Ali and the people who accompany him arrived last
Tuesday in Havana with a medical supplies donation worth more
than one million U.S. dollars. They will return on Saturday to
their home country. 
