<HEADLINE> CIS Leaders Make Positive Comments on Premiership of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the Commonwealth of
Independent States (CIS) have issued positive comments on the new
premiership of Russia after its approval by the Russian lower
house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
In a congratulatory message to the new Russian premier, Yevgeny
Primakov, Saturday, Belarussian President Alexander Lukashenko
described Primakov as "an outstanding statesman" and "talented
scholar and diplomat."
</P>
<P>
Primakov has always supported the friendship between Russia and
Belarus and has long used his rich experience to make
contributions to Russia and the common cause between Russia and
Belarus, Lukashenko said.
</P>
<P>
Tajik President Emomali Rakhmonov Saturday expressed his
confidence that Primakov will be able to unite the whole society
of Russia in getting out of the political and economic crises,
according to media reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The appointment of Primakov as the new premier will not only be
conducive to the mutual understanding among all circles in Russia,
but will also be beneficial to the strengthening of the strategic
partnership between Russia and Tajikistan, Rakhmonov said.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the Russian State Duma, or the lower house of
parliament, overwhelmingly confirmed Primakov on Friday, Armenian
President Robert Kocharyan described Primakov as "an experienced
statesman," saying that Primakov will be able to find a solution
to the current crises faced by Russia.
</P>
<P>
Moldovan President Peter Luchinsky also sent a congratulatory
message to Primakov Saturday, saying that the traditional friendly
relations between Moldova and Russia will further develop toward
mutually beneficiary cooperation after Primakov assumed the
premiership.
</P>
<P>
Luchinsky said that Primakov will continue to implement
Russia's policy of reform.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin named Primakov as premier's
nominee on Thursday after the State Duma rejected Viktor
Chernomyrdin as candidate for prime minister twice. Russian State
Duma on Friday endorsed Primakov's nomination as prime minister by
an overwhelmingly majority. 
</P>
