<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prices of China's Imported Commodities Rise as Smuggling Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Prices of China's imported
commodities have risen sharply since the central government
initiated a nationwide anti-smuggling campaign in early August,
reported today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The paper says that the cost of imported cigarettes, for
example, has gone up by 28 percent in Beijing, while films,
another popular import item, climbing up 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
"The anti-smuggling campaign has almost cut off my imported
cigarette supply," said one grocery store owner.
</P>
<P>
The campaign which involves efforts from customs, police and
industrial and commercial administrations has effectively boosted
prices of major imported commodities, such as automobiles, refined
oil and chemicals.
</P>
<P>
The computer market was among the "hardest-hit" in the drive
with component prices soaring last month. Prices for computer
chips and CPUs went up by an average of 20 percent for the period.
</P>
<P>
However, there are some retailers who have adopted a
wait-and-see strategy, maintaining the original price of imported
commodities.
</P>
<P>
"The films here, including Kodak and Fuji, are all sold at the
same prices for the benefit of our customers," said Yang Guangwei,
general manager of Beijing Red Ribbon Film Store.
</P>
<P>
An official with the State Tobacco Monopoly Bureau said that
the price rise of imported cigarettes will do little to raise the
retail prices for domestic brands because the country's tobacco
market is oversupplied.
</P>
<P>
Experts point out that although consumers suffer losses in a
short term in the price rise, they will later enjoy better product
quality, as the anti-smuggling drive is helpful to establishing a
normal production and sales environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
