<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Intelligence Coordinating Board Head Replaced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The head of Indonesia's State
Intelligence Coordinating Board (Bakin) has been replaced, the
Jakarta Post Saturday quoted Minister/State Secretary Akbar
Tandjung as saying.
</P>
<P>
The minister said President B.J. Habibie has promoted his loyal
advisor Lieutenant General (ret.) Zaini Azhar Maulani to replace
Moetojib as head of the Bakin.
</P>
<P>
The replacement of Moetojib was merely routine because he had
held the position for three years, Akbar said.
</P>
<P>
He dismissed speculation that Moetojib's failure to give
accurate reports on the current wave of student demonstrations was
the main reason for his replacement.
</P>
<P>
Students this week have stepped up protests against the
government for its inability to control the rising prices of
essential commodities.
</P>
<P>
Bakin is directly under the president's supervision and falls
under the State Secretariat administratively. The board's main
responsibility is to monitor foreign affairs and developments.
</P>
<P>
The Armed Forces has its own intelligence body, the BIA, which
is in charge of monitoring the domestic security situation.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted reliable sources as saying that it was quite
natural that Habibie preferred Bakin to be headed by his own
trusted aide, especially since as a civilian he did not know much
about the agency.
</P>
<P>
Maulani was born on January 6, 1939 in South Kalimantan. During
his period of active military service, Maulani was deemed one of
the Armed Forces' most promising officers as a result of his
intellectual capability.
</P>
<P>
He served as Habibie's advisor when Habibie was state minister
of research and technology and he also became a military
columnist.
</P>
<P>
Maulani was then appointed secretary to the vice president, a
job he kept even after Habibie replaced president Soeharto in May.
He received the honorary title of lieutenant general (ret.) in
April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980913.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aston Villa Lead English Premier League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Merson made the breakthrough in the first half and, after
Wimbledon's Carl Leaburn was sent off, Ian Taylor sealed the
three points with the home side's second.
</P>
<P>
With the victory, Aston Villa jumped to the lead in the team
standings over Liverpool with three points clear.
</P>
<P>
Liverpool, who had 10 points from five matches, lost to West
Ham United 2-1 at Upton Park. John Hartson and Israeli Eyal
Berkovic scored the Hammers' goals, with Karlheinz Riedle pulling
one back for Liverpool.
</P>
<P>
Leeds, with a 0-0 draw at Everton, was third in the standings.
</P>
<P>
At Villa Park, John Gregory's side struggled early on to break
down a determined Wimbledon side, who started the day in fourth
place.
</P>
<P>
When Alan Thompson missed his second penalty of the season
after 36 minutes it looked like it wouldn't be Villa's day.
</P>
<P>
Right on half-time Villa earned a second spotkick when Leaburn
elbowed Ugo Ehiogu off the ball.
</P>
<P>
Leaburn was sent off and Merson, signed last week for 6.75
million pounds from Middlesbrough, stepped up to take the
penalty, only for Wimbledon's Neil Sullivan to parry his weak
effort. Fortunately for Merson, Sullivan couldn't hold the ball
and the England international gratefully converted the rebound.
</P>
<P>
From then on Villa controlled the match and Taylor fired home
a cross from the excellent Julian Joachim after 57 minutes to
seal a comfortable victory.
</P>
<P>
West Ham's Hartson and his old Arsenal team mate Ian Wright,
made captain for the day, were a constant menace against
Liverpool.
</P>
<P>
Hartson opened the scoring after just four minutes, his header
from a corner deflecting off Jamie Carragher and in.
</P>
<P>
Liverpool surged back at the start of the second half but were
caught on the counter after 51 minutes when Berkovic fired home
from 20 yards after good work from Hartson.
</P>
<P>
Substitute Riedle hit a post and then pulled one back for Live
rpool with a trademark header in the final minute.
</P>
<P>
"It was important we won after the game in midweek but we were
hanging on for grim life at the end," said West Ham coach Harry
Redknapp, whose side threw away a 3-0 lead to lose 4-3 at home to
Wimbledon on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Manchester United are fifth with eight points and a game in
hand after Dwight Yorke scored his third goal in two games as
they saw off Coventry 2-0 at Old Trafford. Norwegian Ronny
Johnsen scored United's second.
</P>
<P>
Stephen Hughes scored a late but spectacular 35-yard equaliser
for champions Arsenal to grab a 1-1 draw at Leicester. It was the
misfiring Gunners' fourth successive league draw. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
