<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Davenport Beats Hingis to Win U.S. Open Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Second seed Lindsay
Davenport of the United States beat world number one Martina
Hingis of Switzerland to win her first Grand Slam title at the
U.S. Open tennis championships here Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Playing in her first Grand Slam final, Davenport smashed
forehand and backhand winners down the lines and won 12 of the
last 15 points to gain a 6-3, 7-5 victory over the defending
champion.
</P>
<P>
The 22-year-old, the first American-born women's champion at
the U.S. Open since 1982, did not lose a set in the seven rounds
of the tournament, winning 700,000 U.S. dollars for the first
prize.
</P>
<P>
The victory is a sweet gift for her mother's birthday. "I
guess she thinks she's getting a really nice gift now," Davenport
said as she accepted the check, breaking into a laugh when she
looked at her mom in the players' box.
</P>
<P>
After hitting a backhand volley winner on match point, the
champion put her hands on her head in disbelief, then looked
lovingly at her racket before smiling at her mom.
</P>
<P>
"It's just a great story. She's the one that used to drive me
hours and hours to practice, since I was 6 when I started playing
tennis," Davenport said.
</P>
<P>
This is the first year since 1990 that four different women
have won the Grand Slam singles titles.
</P>
<P>
Davenport got an early service break for a 2-1 lead in the
first set by dictating play with sharp volleys and passing shots.
Hingis was handcufffed by the wildness that bothered her
throughout the tournament.
</P>
<P>
In the seventh game, at deuce, Davenport got a break when the
wind knocked off her white baseball cap as she hit the ball into
the net on a tough volley. Davenport won the replay to move to
break point.
</P>
<P>
Hingis looked on in dismay, then lost the next point to give
Davenport another service break for a 5-2 lead. When she came
back from the changeover, Davenport had secured her cap with
bobby pins.
</P>
<P>
Davenport, who moved past Novotna to No. 2 in the world
rankings, wrapped up the first set in 37 minutes with a backhand
on the line.
</P>
<P>
Hingis seemed frustrated at times during the second
set,dropping her racket on the court after losing one point and
screaming at herself after another.
</P>
<P>
Davenport broke for a 4-2 lead but Hingis broke right back and
again for a 5-4 lead. But Davenport regained control, breaking
back as Hingis ended the 10th game with a double fault and shook
her head in dismay.
</P>
<P>
Davenport held serve in the last game and finished off the
match with a clever shot.
</P>
<P>
Davenport and Hingis will face each other Sunday in the
women's doubles final. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
