<P>
MOSCOW -- The appointment of Yevgeny Primakov as prime minister
was an unequivocal proof of Russia's commitment to a free market
course, said Russian President Boris Yeltsin in a telephone
conversation with U.S. President Bill Clinton on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Russian presidential press service said in a statement that
Yeltsin stressed the permanence of Russia's foreign policy,
including a mutually beneficial and equal partnership with the
United States; the consistency in the carrying out of reforms; and
the lack of an alternative to a market course.
</P>
