<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rafter, Philippoussis to Meet in U.S. Open Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion Patrick
Rafter spoiled American Pete Sampra's bid for a record-tying 12th
Grand Slam title as he capitalized on a leg injury to upset the
top seed and four-time winner 6-7 (8-10), 6-4, 2-6, 6-4, 6-3 in
the semifinal of the U.S. Open tennis championships here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Rafter will attempt to win his second consecutive U.S. Open
title Sunday against fellow Australian Mark Philippoussis, who
beat 10th seed Carlos Moya of Spain 6-1, 6-4, 5-7, 6-4 in another
semifinal. It will be the first time two Australians fight in the
Open's final since 1970.
</P>
<P>
Sampras appeared to be in control of the match late in the
third set when he sustained an injury to his upper left thign. He
managed to hold on to win the final game of the set, but was
unable to move at a normal pace for the remainder of the match.
</P>
<P>
Sampras was hardly competitive after the injury, especially
returning serve. In the fourth set, Rafter broke in the opening
game and that was all he needed as Sampras never really
threatened to break back.
</P>
<P>
Rafter broke again to build a 2-0 lead in the fifth set and
Sampras, whose strong serve was the only weapon he could rely on,
faded in the final service game. He fell on match point as Rafter
unleashed a wicked backhand passing shot to seal the victory.
</P>
<P>
"I could see he was having problems," said Rafter. "I tried to
keep the ball away from him as best as possible. I didn't want to
hit it right at him. He could still hit winners but I saw he was
having a bit of a problem with his mobility."
</P>
<P>
Sampras sustained the injury serving at 4-2 in the third set
and apparently in control of the match after breaking Rafter. He
dashed to the net to hit a volley and his left leg appeared to
buckle after the shot. Sampras grabbed the leg in pain and left
the court with a trainer for treatment after holding for a 5-2
lead.
</P>
<P>
The meeting between Rafter and Sampras was their 11th but
their first in Grand Slam play. Sampras lost to Rafter for only
the third time and suffered his eighth defeat in 64 matches
lifetime against Australian opponents.
</P>
<P>
Rafter nearly became the first defending champion to go out in
the first round the following year as he rallied from two sets
down to beat Hicham Arazi of Morocco.
</P>
<P>
Rafter improved to 8-0 this year against players ranked in the
top 10 and won his 10th consecutive five-set match.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Rafter will attempt to become only the sixth player
in the Open Era to successfully defend his U.S. Open title.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
