<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippoussis Beats Moya in U.S. Open Semifinal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Unseeded Mark Philippoussis
of Australia beat 10th seed Carlos Moya of Spain 6-1, 6-4, 5-7,
6-4 to advance to his first Grand Slam final at the U.S. Open
tennis championships here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Philippoussis, one of the hardest servers in tennis,
overpowered Moya, who was attempting to pull off a rare double in
winning the French Open and the U.S. Open in the same year.
Philippoussis had 21 aces with 11 double faults and 75 winners
against 36 unforced errors. Moya, meanwhile, managed only six
aces and recorded only 32 winners while making 12 unforced errors.
</P>
<P>
"I've been working extremely hard on my all-around game," said
Philippoussis. "I've been spending a lot more time on the court
than normal, just working on all parts of my game. I concentrated
extremely well. I applied the pressure on him. He felt the
pressure. I just served great. Right now, I honestly feel like no
one can beat me. I can win this thing."
</P>
<P>
Philippoussis broke Moya twice and won the opening set in only
20 minutes and needed only another 31 minutes to capture the
second, breaking to go up 4-2, and serving out the set. But Moya
rallied in the third set after fending off four break points at
5-5. Moya held to 6-5 and then took the set on two consecutive
double faults by Philippoussis.
</P>
<P>
Moya fought to 2-2 in the fourth set but could not work his
way out. He was called three times for foot faults.
</P>
<P>
"Three foot faults in one game when they didn't call one the
whole match," said Moya. "I don't know what to think anymore.
There was another call the woman missed. I'm sorry to say but
that woman was a little bit old. The ball was like 130 mph. I
thought it was out. How can she see the ball? No way!"
</P>
<P>
After Moya saved two match points at 4-5, Philippoussis ended
the match in one hour 50 minutes with a crisp backhand volley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980913.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Says, Starr Report Not Ground for Impeachment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Vice President Al
Gore said Saturday that Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's report
to Congress is not grounds for impeachment of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"I do not believe this report serves as the basis for
overturning the judgment of the American people ... that Bill
Clinton should be their president," Gore said after ceremonies
opening a light-rail line into this Portland suburb in Oregon.
</P>
<P>
"He has accepted responsibility for his actions. He has said he
did wrong. He has asked for forgiveness. He has addressed the
issues he needs to address," media reports quoted Gore as saying.
</P>
<P>
Gore, making a weekend swing through Portland and Seattle to
speak on environmental issues and campaign for congressional
candidates, made no mention of the Starr report in his remarks to
a crowd of 2,000.
</P>
<P>
But in a short statement to reporters afterward, he stressed he
would not abandon the president in his darkest hours.
</P>
<P>
"For almost six years now, I have served alongside this
president as he has led us toward unprecedented prosperity, toward
solutions to problems we need to address," Gore said. "He is
doing a tremendous job as president. I look forward to beginning
to work with him as we continue to address the issues that face
this country."  
</P>
</TEXT>
