<HEADLINE> U.S. Welcomes Bosnia-Croatia Deal on Port </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States on
Saturday welcomed a deal reached between Bosnia and Croatia, which
would allow Bosnia to use the Croatian port of Ploce and give
Croatia transit through the town of Neum.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. welcomes the successful conclusion of negotiations...
regarding Bosnian use of the Port of Ploce and Croatian transit
through Neum," State Department spokesman James Rubin said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
The agreement "represents an effort by both countries to put
aside the mistrust of the past and look to a new era of economic
cooperation."
</P>
<P>
"Croatian President (Franjo) Tudjman and Bosnian President
(Alija) Izetbegovic are to be commended for their contributions
that made possible the initialing of this important agreement,"
Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. looks forward to an early signature and ratification
of the Ploce/Neum agreement by both countries," he added.
</P>
<P>
The two sides reached a draft agreement last weekend, giving
Bosnia the right to free transit to and from Ploce port on the
Adriatic sea.
</P>
<P>
Ploce was the main port used by the country when it was part of
federal Yugoslavia for transporting raw materials and industrial
products.
</P>
<P>
The right for Bosnia to use the port was granted by the 1995
Dayton peace agreement, signed by all the parties involved in the
civil war in Bosnia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
