<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Issues Second Rebuttal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 12 (Xinhua) -- A day after the release of
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's report, the White House fought
back Saturday with a second rebuttal, calling the prosecutor's
allegations a "hit-and-run smear campaign" lacking legal merit.
</P>
<P>
"It is plain that 'sex' is precisely what this four-and-a-half
year investigation has boiled down to," the White House argued in
its second counter report.
</P>
<P>
"The referral is so loaded with irrelevant and unnecessary
graphic and salacious allegations that only one conclusion is
possible: its principal purpose is to damage the President," the
rebuttal said.
</P>
<P>
While President Clinton's actions were wrong, the acts
described by prosecutors "do not even approach the Constitutional
test of impeachment," Clinton's White House and private lawyers
argued. Their report provided a point-by-point rejection of the 11
grounds for possible impeachment cited in Starr's referral made
public Friday.
</P>
<P>
In Atlanta, House Speaker Newt Gingrich said the lurid nature
of the report was unfortunate but caused by the president's denial
of a sexual relationship with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky. He called on lawmakers to reserve judgment.
</P>
<P>
"I think you cannot render... any judgment until you have given
the president a chance to respond and given the Judiciary
Committee a chance to do its job," Gingrich said.
</P>
<P>
Starr's allegations are "simply part of a hit-and-run smear
campaign, and their inclusion says volumes about the
(prosecutor's) tactics and objectives," the White House said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, in his weekly radio address Saturday, said it had been
"an exhausting and difficult week in the capital -- not only for
me, but for many others." Without a mention of the Starr report,
he pledged to press ahead with his policy agenda.
</P>
<P>
"The most important thing to do now is to stay focused on the
issues the American people sent us here to deal with, from health
care to the economy to terrorism," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Lawmakers this weekend were home campaigning and listening to
voters. The next set of jurors on the case, members of the House
Judiciary Committee charged with deciding whether impeachment
proceedings are warranted, reacted cautiously.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously he did something wrong," said Representative Thomas
Barrett, a Democrat who was appointed to the committee on Friday.
"I want to see what the evidence is with regard to the other
allegations and listen to what the president has to say and then
make a decision as to what is right for the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
Representative Steve Rothman, a Democrat said, "I'm not going
to make my decision about whether to impeach the president from
newspaper accounts of documents that I'm eventually going to be
presented."
</P>
<P>
Republicans disagreed with White House arguments there was
nothing worthy of impeachment in the report, but they too were
careful not to predict whether proceedings would begin.
</P>
<P>
"Even those defenders of the president who sought to diminish
the significance of perjury in a civil case have acknowledged that
it's simply unacceptable for a president to lie before a grand
jury," said Representatives Charles Canady, a Republican, another
Judiciary Committee member. "I am reserving judgment on all these
matters." 
</P>
</TEXT>
